    "evidence_passages": [
      "The equations are discretized on a C-grid using a finite volume technique which has excellent conservation properties.",
      "The finite volume form ensures that discrete integral properties such as conservation of mass and heat are maintained exactly to machine precision."
    ],
    "justification": "The paper explicitly states that the model uses a finite volume technique, which is a method designed for strict conservation. The authors further claim that this method ensures integral properties like mass and heat are conserved \"exactly to machine precision.\" This is a clear statement of strictly closed budgets, which directly aligns with the criteria for Level 3.",
    "paper_doi": "10.1016/B978-044482322-9/50121-3",
    "paper_title": "Application of a parallel Navier-Stokes model to ocean circulation"
  },
  {
    "dimension": "data_integration",
    "has_evidence": true,
    "evidence_level": 1,
    "evidence_passages": [
      "The model is driven by monthly mean wind-stresses derived from the analysis of Hellerman and Rosenstein [7] and relaxed toward the monthly mean sea-surface-temperature and salinity climatologies of Levitus [8]."
    ],
    "justification": "The paper describes an application where the ocean model is 'driven by' observed wind-stress data and its surface temperature and salinity are 'relaxed toward' climatological data sets. This method, often called nudging or relaxation, uses observational data as a direct forcing term in the model equations. This fits the description of a Level 1 (Forced) system, where the model is driven by data, and the physics can be violated by the addition of these non-physical source/sink terms.",
    "paper_doi": "10.1016/B978-044482322-9/50121-3",
    "paper_title": "Application of a parallel Navier-Stokes model to ocean circulation"
  },
  {
    "dimension": "verification",
    "has_evidence": true,
    "evidence_level": 2,
    "evidence_passages": [
      "The parallel code has also been shown to give statistically identical results to the original vector code on which it is based (the MITgcm) in a variety of test calculations.",
      "We have repeated the baroclinic eddy experiment of McWilliams [5] in a periodic channel on the \u03b2-plane.",
      "Our parameter settings are identical to the rotating convection experiment #1 of Jones and Marshall [6]. ... A detailed comparison with the results of Jones and Marshall reveals a close correspondence in the gross statistics of the flow (such as the basin-averaged heat flux and kinetic energy)."
    ],
    "justification": "The paper provides evidence of structured verification by comparing the parallel model against both a prior version of the code and established numerical benchmarks. The authors state that the parallel code gives 'statistically identical results to the original vector code', which constitutes a regression test. Furthermore, the model is tested on standard idealized problems, such as the baroclinic eddy experiment of McWilliams and a rotating convection experiment, and results are compared to those previously published. These activities\u2014regression testing and comparison against standard benchmarks\u2014are forms of structured testing that fit the criteria for Level 2.",
    "paper_doi": "10.1016/B978-044482322-9/50121-3",
    "paper_title": "Application of a parallel Navier-Stokes model to ocean circulation"
  },
  {
    "dimension": "validation",
    "has_evidence": true,
    "evidence_level": 1,
    "evidence_passages": [
      "Note the meandering of the Gulf Stream and Kuroshio extensions and the rich eddy fields in the Antarctic Circumpolar Current. These are qualitatively in accord with observations.",
      "The simulated stream separates from the coast at Cape Hatteras, forms tight, vigorous meanders which grow in amplitude downstream, and sheds warm and cold core rings... All these features are observed in the real ocean.",
      "A map of the eddy kinetic energy (EKE) at 100m is plotted in Fig.4. The patterns of EKE are in broad agreement with those deduced from satellite altimetry ... although the simulated levels are somewhat lower than observed, a deficiency that is common to all GCMs of the ocean."
    ],
    "justification": "The paper provides evidence for Level 1 validation by making qualitative comparisons of the model's output to real-world observations. The authors state that simulated features like the Gulf Stream, Kuroshio extension, and eddy fields are 'qualitatively in accord with observations'. They also note that simulated eddy kinetic energy patterns are in 'broad agreement' with satellite altimetry data. These comparisons are based on visual inspection ('eyeball fits') and descriptive language rather than quantitative statistical metrics (Level 2) or rigorous process-level validation against independent datasets (Level 3).",
    "paper_doi": "10.1016/B978-044482322-9/50121-3",
    "paper_title": "Application of a parallel Navier-Stokes model to ocean circulation"
  },
  {
    "dimension": "uncertainty_quantification",
