    "evidence_level": null,
    "evidence_passages": [],
    "justification": "The paper focuses entirely on the technical implementation and computational performance of a parallel Navier-Stokes model for ocean circulation. It describes the model's parallelization strategy, domain decomposition, and performance metrics on various supercomputers. While it presents results from a world ocean simulation as a demonstration, it does not perform any uncertainty analysis, sensitivity studies, or quantification of confidence in the results. The text does not contain any mention of ensembles, error bounds (in the UQ sense), or probabilistic methods.",
    "paper_doi": "10.1016/B978-044482322-9/50121-3",
    "paper_title": "Application of a parallel Navier-Stokes model to ocean circulation"
  },
  {
    "dimension": "numerical_fidelity",
    "has_evidence": true,
    "evidence_level": 1,
    "evidence_passages": [
      "The equations are mapped on to a regular latitude-longitude grid and discretized using a finite difference method.",
      "The model domain is an idealised rectangular basin, 2000 km x 3000 km, with a flat bottom 5 km deep.",
      "The horizontal resolution is 20 km... The lateral boundary conditions are 'no-slip' on the solid walls and 'free-slip' on the open northern and southern boundaries."
    ],
    "justification": "The paper describes a model implementation that uses a 'regular latitude-longitude grid', which is a static grid. The application discussed uses an 'idealised rectangular basin' with a 'flat bottom' and simple 'no-slip' or 'free-slip' lateral boundary conditions. This combination of a static grid and simplified boundaries directly corresponds to the criteria for Level 1: 'Coarse: Low-resolution static grids; simplified boundaries'. There is no evidence of nested grids, regional refinement, or dynamic boundaries (Levels 2 or 3).",
    "paper_doi": "10.1016/B978-044482322-9/50121-3",
    "paper_title": "Application of a parallel Navier-Stokes model to ocean circulation"
  },
  {
    "dimension": "portability_scaling",
