      "The major issue that has driven much of the work in this area has been the desire to perform numerical calculations in a finite domain that accurately reflect the flow in an infinite or semi-infinite domain.",
      "One of the earliest and still widely used methods is to introduce a \u201csponge\u201d layer at the outflow boundary (Israeli & Orszag 1981). In this region, which must be large enough to contain several wavelengths of the dominant, outgoing waves, the governing equations are modified by adding terms that will damp any wave that enters it.",
      "A more popular method for specifying the outflow boundary condition is to assume that close to the boundary the flow is governed by a simple wave equation... For numerical calculations, the use of such a condition, first proposed by Orlanski (1976), has become commonplace."
    ],
    "justification": "The paper is a review of methods for handling \"open boundaries\" in numerical simulations. These boundaries are by definition artificial constructs used to truncate a computational domain that represents a physically larger or infinite space. The paper discusses common techniques like \"sponge layers\" and wave-equation-based conditions (e.g., Orlanski's condition), which are methods for managing these computationally necessary, simplified boundaries. The focus is on the mathematical conditions at these static, artificial boundaries, which falls under the \"simplified boundaries\" criterion of Level 1. The paper does not discuss realistic topography, nested/refined grids (Level 2), or dynamic/moving boundaries (Level 3).",
