    "evidence_passages": [
      "The goal of this thesis is to quantify this uncertainty in the model-predicted ocean state. We develop and implement a method for estimating the evolution of the uncertainty in the model solution, as described by its error covariance matrix.",
      "The error in the model solution is defined as e = x - x_t. We assume that the error is a random variable with zero mean and covariance P = E[ee^T], where E denotes the expectation operator.",
      "The problem is to find an estimate of the error covariance matrix P(t) at any time t, given the initial error covariance P(t_0) and a model of the error sources. The evolution of the error covariance matrix is governed by the Lyapunov equation, dP/dt = AP + PA^T + Q, where Q is the covariance matrix of the model errors."
    ],
    "justification": "The paper presents a formal probabilistic framework for quantifying uncertainty. It explicitly defines model error as a random variable and aims to compute its error covariance matrix, P. The evolution of this covariance matrix is governed by a formal mathematical equation (the Lyapunov equation). This approach directly models the probability distribution of the error (specifically, its second moment), which is a hallmark of Level 3 probabilistic uncertainty quantification.",
