      "The parameterization presented in this thesis is based on the idea of potential vorticity mixing, first proposed by Rhines and Young (1982a). The advantage of this approach is that it is formulated in a way that is consistent with the known dynamics of the system. In particular, it is formulated in terms of a flux of potential vorticity, which is a conserved quantity. This means that the scheme itself is conservative, and does not introduce spurious sources or sinks of potential vorticity.",
      "The parameterization is formulated in terms of a flux of potential vorticity, so it is guaranteed to conserve the total potential vorticity in the domain.",
