  {
    "dimension": "data_integration",
    "has_evidence": true,
    "evidence_level": 3,
    "evidence_passages": [
      "The proposed scheme is based on a stochastic formulation of the inverse problem, combining a priori information about the unknown sound-speed field with the information content of the traveltime data.",
      "The solution p to the nonlinear inverse problem is taken to be the parameter vector that minimizes the cost function J(p) = [T_calc(p) \u2212 T_meas]^T R\u22121 [T_calc(p) \u2212 T_meas] + (p \u2212 p_prior)^T P\u22121 (p \u2212 p_prior), where T_calc are the traveltimes calculated for the parameter vector p, and T_meas are the measured traveltimes.",
      "In this work a different approach is presented, which is not based on iterative linearization. Instead, the nonlinear character of the problem is fully taken into account, and the inversion is performed in a single step by minimizing a nonlinear cost function."
    ],
    "justification": "The paper describes a variational data assimilation method that finds the optimal model state (sound-speed field) by minimizing a single cost function. This cost function mathematically combines the mismatch between model-calculated and observed data with the mismatch between the solution and a prior physical state, weighted by their respective error covariances. This formulation, where the final state is a simultaneous synthesis of observations and model physics/priors, is the definition of a Level 3 approach. The data and physics are mathematically inseparable in the cost function, which is the core characteristic of Level 3. While not explicitly 4D-Var, this non-linear variational analysis method is a form of 3D-Var, which belongs to the same class of advanced synthesis techniques.",
    "paper_doi": "10.1175/1520-0426(2000)017<0240:OSAONT>2.0.CO;2",
