    "evidence_passages": [
      "The tomographic problem is to find a model m that minimizes the cost function S(m) = [d - g(m)]^T W [d - g(m)] + (m - m_a)^T V^{-1} (m - m_a), where m_a is the a priori estimate of the model parameters and V the a priori model covariance matrix.",
      "The uncertainty of the solution is given by the a posteriori model covariance matrix V' = (G^T W G + V^{-1})^{-1}, where G is the Frechet derivative (or sensitivity matrix) of the forward model calculated at the solution m.",
      "The square roots of the diagonal elements of V' are the standard deviations of the estimated model parameters, that is, the inversion errors."
    ],
    "justification": "The paper employs a formal probabilistic approach to uncertainty quantification rooted in inverse theory. It formulates the problem using a cost function that includes an 'a priori model covariance matrix' (V), which is equivalent to specifying a prior distribution in a Bayesian context. The authors then explicitly calculate the 'a posteriori model covariance matrix' (V') to quantify the uncertainty of their solution. They state that the 'square roots of the diagonal elements of V'' represent the standard deviations or inversion errors. This calculation of a posterior covariance matrix, which characterizes the uncertainty of the model parameters, is a hallmark of a Level 3 (Probabilistic) approach to UQ.",
    "paper_doi": "10.1175/1520-0426(2000)017<0240:OSAONT>2.0.CO;2",
    "paper_title": "One-step analysis of non-linear traveltime data in ocean acoustic tomography"
  },
