  {
    "dimension": "physics_conservation",
    "has_evidence": true,
    "evidence_level": 2,
    "evidence_passages": [
      "Many models, instead of using fluxes, restore the surface temperature and salinity to observed climatological values (Haney, 1971; Barnier et al., 1995). A problem with this approach is that the fluxes required to maintain the climatology can be large and unrealistic. For climate studies, it is much better to use specified fluxes of heat and fresh water, possibly with a small restoring term to prevent the model drifting too far from the observed state.",
      "The non-linear momentum advection terms are usually discretised using a scheme that conserves energy and enstrophy (Arakawa, 1966). However, in a Boussinesq model it is not possible to conserve both volume and energy, and in most models it is volume that is conserved.",
      "With global warming, it is essential that climate models are able to correctly simulate changes in heat content and the transport of heat. This requires careful consideration of the energy budget. One source of problems is the Boussinesq approximation... Another problem is that some numerical schemes can be noisy... The net effect can be to add or remove heat from the ocean, creating a 'leak' in the global heat budget."
    ],
    "justification": "The paper provides clear evidence for Level 2. The models are based on primary physics (the primitive equations, which are statements of conservation). There is a strong awareness and monitoring of global budgets, as shown by the discussion of the energy budget and the concern over creating a \"'leak' in the global heat budget.\" However, these budgets are not strictly enforced. The common practice of using \"a small restoring term to prevent the model drifting\" is an explicit admission of a non-physical flux (a 'nudge' or 'leak') being introduced to the system to keep it stable. Furthermore, the paper notes that due to the Boussinesq approximation, it's not possible to strictly conserve both volume and energy simultaneously, indicating a known and accepted imperfection in closing all budgets. This aligns perfectly with the Level 2 criteria of \"Primary physics present; global budgets monitored but not strictly enforced.\"",
    "paper_doi": "10.1016/S1463-5003(00)00014-7",
    "paper_title": "Developments in ocean climate modelling"
  },
  {
    "dimension": "data_integration",
    "has_evidence": true,
    "evidence_level": 3,
    "evidence_passages": [
      "More advanced methods have been developed which use either sequential methods, based on the Kalman filter and its simplifications (e.g. Bennett, 1992; Evensen, 1994; Fukumori, Raghunath, & Fu, 1998), or variational methods based on control theory and adjoint models (Le Dimet & Talagrand, 1986; Thacker & Long, 1988).",
      "The variational approach finds the model solution which is closest to the observations over a period of time. It requires the development of the adjoint of the numerical model, which is a major task for a complex ocean general circulation model.",
      "For example, the ECCO (Estimating the Circulation and Climate of the Ocean) project is making good progress using the adjoint of the MIT GCM (Marotzke, Giering, Zhang, Stammer, Hill, & Lee, 1999)."
    ],
    "justification": "The paper provides a comprehensive overview of data assimilation techniques in ocean modeling, covering methods that correspond to all three levels. However, it explicitly describes the most advanced methods available at the time, which align with Level 3. The paper mentions \"sequential methods, based on the Kalman filter\" (Level 2), but contrasts them with more sophisticated \"variational methods based on control theory and adjoint models.\" This latter approach, which finds a model solution that best fits observations over a time period, is a clear description of 4D-Var, a Level 3 'Synthesis' technique where data and model physics are mathematically inseparable. The paper further notes that major projects like ECCO were actively and successfully using these adjoint-based methods, confirming that this was a state-of-the-art practice and not just a theoretical concept.",
    "paper_doi": "10.1016/S1463-5003(00)00014-7",
    "paper_title": "Developments in ocean climate modelling"
  },
  {
    "dimension": "verification",
    "has_evidence": true,
    "evidence_level": 3,
    "evidence_passages": [
      "A hierarchy of tests is required, ranging from studies of the numerical integrity of the code on idealized problems to simulations of the full global ocean circulation for comparison with observations.",
      "Idealized test cases are particularly useful for isolating the effects of particular parameterizations or numerical schemes, and are an important part of the code development and verification process. Examples of such tests include simulations of flow over a seamount (e.g. Beckmann and Haidvogel, 1993; Smith et al., in press), lock exchange problems (e.g. Hallberg, 1995), wind-driven gyres (e.g. Roberts et al., 1996) and convection in a closed basin (e.g. Jones and Marshall, 1993).",
      "A notable problem with sigma-coordinate models concerns the unphysical flows which can arise from errors in computing the horizontal pressure gradient force (e.g. Haney, 1991; Mellor et al., 1994). This error arises from the subtraction of two large and nearly equal terms, and it can be especially large in regions of steep topography. Much work has gone into reducing this error (e.g. Song, 1998; Shchepetkin and McWilliams, submitted)."
    ],
    "justification": "The paper explicitly describes a \"code development and verification process\" that uses a \"hierarchy of tests\" to ensure \"numerical integrity\". It provides examples of \"idealized test cases\" (e.g., wind-driven gyres, flow over a seamount) that function as standard benchmarks to verify the implementation of numerical schemes. Some of these idealized problems have known analytical or semi-analytical solutions, qualifying them as exact benchmarks. Additionally, the paper discusses active research into identifying and reducing specific numerical errors, such as the pressure gradient force error, which demonstrates a rigorous approach to ensuring the mathematical correctness of the algorithms. This use of idealized benchmarks and focused error analysis to verify the core algorithms aligns with the Level 3 criteria.",
    "paper_doi": "10.1016/S1463-5003(00)00014-7",
    "paper_title": "Developments in ocean climate modelling"
  },
  {
    "dimension": "validation",
    "has_evidence": true,
    "evidence_level": 3,
    "evidence_passages": [
      "The classic method to assess the realism of ocean simulations is to compare the time mean state of the simulated ocean with gridded climatological data sets, such as those from Levitus et al. (1998) or the World Ocean Atlas (Antonov et al., 1998). [...] Although useful, a more objective and quantitative method is to compute difference fields and scalar metrics such as the root mean square (RMS) error and mean bias.",
      "One of the best tests of an ocean model\u2019s ability to simulate large-scale transport on decadal time-scales is to examine its uptake and redistribution of anthropogenic transient tracers, such as CFCs or tritium.",
      "These tracers have well-known atmospheric histories and surface boundary conditions, and their distributions in the ocean interior have been extensively measured as part of programs such as WOCE and GEOSECS.",
      "A further test of model fidelity is to examine its ability to simulate observed climate variability. For example, models are now being run with historical forcing for the last 50 years and compared with the observed records of ENSO."
    ],
    "justification": "The paper describes a hierarchy of validation techniques. It mentions comparisons to climatologies using both qualitative plots (Level 1) and quantitative metrics like RMS error and bias (Level 2). However, it goes further to describe more sophisticated, process-level validation, which meets the Level 3 criteria. Specifically, it highlights the use of independent, global datasets of anthropogenic tracers (CFCs from WOCE/GEOSECS programs) to test the model's ability to simulate the physical process of large-scale transport. Additionally, it discusses running models with historical forcing and comparing simulated variability (like ENSO) against observed records, which constitutes a blind validation against independent data. These process-level tests against independent global datasets are clear evidence for Level 3.",
    "paper_doi": "10.1016/S1463-5003(00)00014-7",
    "paper_title": "Developments in ocean climate modelling"
  },
  {
    "dimension": "uncertainty_quantification",
    "has_evidence": true,
    "evidence_level": 2,
    "evidence_passages": [
      "An important exercise aimed at better understanding model differences has been the `DYNamics of the North Atlantic Models' (DYNAMO) project. The purpose of DYNAMO was to compare three different North Atlantic models...",
      "A set of common experiments has been performed with ten different ocean models of the North Atlantic ... Again, there is a wide spread in the magnitude of the response between the models ... This large spread is an indication of the uncertainty associated with model formulation.",
      "Recently, there have been a number of studies that systematically investigate the sensitivity of a coarse resolution model to parameter changes. They demonstrate the level of sensitivity of the simulated ocean state to various tuneable parameters that are present in all ocean models."
    ],
    "justification": "The paper provides clear evidence for Level 2 Uncertainty Quantification. It describes multi-model intercomparison projects (e.g., DYNAMO) where ensembles of different models are run under common experimental setups. The resulting 'wide spread in the magnitude of the response between the models' is explicitly used as 'an indication of the uncertainty'. Furthermore, the paper discusses 'studies that systematically investigate the sensitivity of a coarse resolution model to parameter changes'. Both using the spread of an ensemble of runs as a proxy for error and performing sensitivity analysis are characteristic methods of Level 2.",
    "paper_doi": "10.1016/S1463-5003(00)00014-7",
    "paper_title": "Developments in ocean climate modelling"
