  {
    "dimension": "numerical_fidelity",
    "has_evidence": true,
    "evidence_level": 3,
    "evidence_passages": [
      "A promising new approach is the Arbitrary Lagrangian\u2013Eulerian (ALE) method, which periodically re-grids the model domain. This approach is very general and can, in principle, be configured to reproduce any of the other coordinate systems. For example, the vertical grid can be configured to be isopycnal in the interior, terrain following near the bottom, and z-like near the surface. Such a hybrid coordinate system is thought by many to be the way forward for ocean climate models.",
      "A more radical approach is to use an unstructured grid... An unstructured grid model allows for enhanced resolution in regions of interest, such as coastal areas, overflows, and deep convection sites, while using coarse resolution elsewhere. Indeed, unstructured grid models are becoming common for regional and coastal applications, but have yet to be applied to global climate problems.",
      "Recent developments of dynamic-thermodynamic sea-ice models have led to more realistic simulations of the Arctic ice cover and its seasonal cycle... Another key element is the representation of ice rheology, which describes how the ice pack deforms and moves under the action of winds and ocean currents."
    ],
    "justification": "The paper, a review of developments in ocean modeling circa 2000, discusses techniques that span all three levels of numerical fidelity but highlights advanced methods that fall into Level 3. The first quote describes the Arbitrary Lagrangian-Eulerian (ALE) method, which supports dynamic, hybrid coordinate systems that adapt vertically (e.g., isopycnal, terrain-following, z-level). This represents a form of dynamic mesh refinement. The second quote discusses unstructured grids that allow for anisotropic mesh refinement, enhancing resolution in specific regions of interest. The third quote describes dynamic sea-ice models that simulate the deformation and movement of the ice pack, which acts as a time-varying, moving boundary for the ocean model. These examples of dynamic grids and moving boundaries are clear evidence for Level 3.",
    "paper_doi": "10.1016/S1463-5003(00)00014-7",
    "paper_title": "Developments in ocean climate modelling"
  },
  {
    "dimension": "portability_scaling",
    "has_evidence": true,
    "evidence_level": 2,
    "evidence_passages": [
      "The need to incorporate more sophisticated physical processes, and to increase resolution, means that ocean models will continue to push the frontiers of high-performance computing. Until recently, this meant making the best use of a small number of fast processors on vector supercomputers. Today it means making effective use of massively parallel computers with a large number of slower processors.",
      "Most modern ocean models are written using a message-passing programming model that allows them to run on a wide variety of parallel computers. However, for efficient use of massively parallel computers, the model algorithms must be rethought to take advantage of the strengths, and to minimize the weaknesses, of the new architectures.",
      "The most important of these is the need to minimize communication amongst the processors, which can form a bottleneck on many machines. For example, the solution of the elliptic boundary value problem for the barotropic streamfunction, a key element of many models, requires information from the whole of the model domain. Its implementation on a parallel computer requires global communication amongst all processors."
    ],
    "justification": "The paper explicitly discusses the shift from vector supercomputers to \"massively parallel computers\" and the use of a \"message-passing programming model\" (the paradigm for MPI) to enable models to \"run on a wide variety of parallel computers.\" It also details the challenges of scaling on these architectures, such as minimizing inter-processor communication. This evidence directly aligns with the Level 2 criteria: \"Parallel: MPI/OpenMP; scales on HPC clusters\". The paper does not mention GPU acceleration or cloud-native approaches, which would be required for Level 3.",
    "paper_doi": "10.1016/S1463-5003(00)00014-7",
    "paper_title": "Developments in ocean climate modelling"
  },
  {
    "dimension": "interoperability",
    "has_evidence": true,
    "evidence_level": 2,
    "evidence_passages": [
      "Most climate models now employ a 'flux coupler' (e.g. Neale and Hoskins, unpublished manuscript, 2000) which serves as an interface between the various model components (e.g. atmosphere, ocean, sea-ice, land). Flux couplers manage the interpolation of fields between the disparate grids employed by the various model components, ensure conservation of exchanged quantities, and compute the various interface fluxes.",
      "The climate modelling community has a long history of coordinated experiments aimed at comparing and assessing models (e.g. the Atmospheric Model Intercomparison Project (AMIP; Gates, 1992) and the Coupled Model Intercomparison Project (CMIP; Meehl et al., 2000)). A related effort is the Ocean Model Intercomparison Project (OMIP) whose focus is on the ocean and sea-ice components of coupled models..."
    ],
    "justification": "The paper provides evidence for Level 2. The first quote explicitly describes the use of 'flux couplers' as a standard practice for interfacing different model components (ocean, atmosphere, sea-ice), which is a clear departure from the 'no coupling interfaces' of Level 1. The second quote describes large-scale Model Intercomparison Projects (CMIP, OMIP) which, by their nature, require standardized data formats and metadata for model outputs to be shared and compared across the community. While the paper does not name a specific format like NetCDF, this was the de facto standard for projects like CMIP at the time (2000). These practices do not meet the Level 3 criteria, which involve more advanced, component-based coupling frameworks like ESMF/NUOPC that were developed after this paper was published.",
    "paper_doi": "10.1016/S1463-5003(00)00014-7",
    "paper_title": "Developments in ocean climate modelling"
  },
