      "The free surface \u03b7(x, y, t) represents the deviation of the ocean surface from the reference geopotential z=0. The free surface is a time-dependent material surface that moves through the fixed vertical grid levels.",
      "The challenge with the explicit free surface in z-coordinate models, as implemented in MOM2 (Pacanowski 1996), arises from the time dependence of the top model-level thickness, which changes as the free surface height \u03b7 evolves.",
      "The thickness of the top model level is given by \u03b4z1(x, y, t) = \u03b7(x, y, t) - z_f(k=1/2), where z_f(k=1/2) is the depth of the interface just below the surface level. The crucial point is that \u03b4z1 is a function of time..."
    ],
    "justification": "The paper focuses on developing and analyzing a numerical method for handling an explicit free surface, which is described as a \"time-dependent material surface\" and a moving top boundary. The entire methodology is built around correctly handling the time-varying thickness of the top model grid cell, which is a direct consequence of this moving boundary. This directly fulfills the \"time-varying/moving boundaries\" criterion for Level 3.",
