    "evidence_passages": [
      "The correctness of the adjoint code has been checked by a standard test, which is detailed in the Appendix.",
      "APPENDIX: Validation of the gradient computation. The standard test to check the correctness of the adjoint code (and thus the correctness of the gradient) consists in comparing the gradient given by the adjoint method with a finite-difference approximation of it. Let J be the cost function, x the control vector and \u03b4x a perturbation. A first-order Taylor expansion gives J (x + \u03b1\u03b4x) \u2248 J (x) + \u03b1\u2207J \u00b7 \u03b4x. We define the ratio \u03c6(\u03b1) = (J(x + \u03b1\u03b4x) \u2212 J(x)) / (\u03b1\u2207J \u00b7 \u03b4x). If the gradient is correct, the first-order Taylor expansion is valid, and the ratio \u03c6(\u03b1) should be close to 1 for small \u03b1.",
      "The results are shown in Table A1. For \u03b1 decreasing from 10\u207b\u00b9 to 10\u207b\u2077, the value of \u03c6 is getting closer and closer to 1. For \u03b1 = 10\u207b\u2078, round-off errors become important and \u03c6 diverges from 1. This test confirms the correctness of the gradient computation."
    ],
    "justification": "The paper provides a dedicated appendix to describe the verification of the adjoint model code. The authors perform a Taylor test (also known as a gradient test) to check the correctness of the gradient calculation, a critical component of their variational assimilation system. They compare the gradient computed by the adjoint code with a finite-difference approximation and show results in a table, demonstrating that the ratio of the two converges to 1 as expected. This type of algorithmic check for gradient accuracy is a specific example of the Level 3 criteria ('Adjoint/Taylor tests for gradient accuracy').",
