  {
    "dimension": "uncertainty_quantification",
    "has_evidence": true,
    "evidence_level": 2,
    "evidence_passages": [
      "The cost-function J to be minimized is the sum of two terms: a background term Jb which measures the distance between the model initial state and a background field (a priori estimate), and an observation term Jo which measures the distance between the model and the observations. They are weighted by the inverse of their respective error covariance matrices. J = Jb + Jo, where Jb = (1/2)(x \u2212 xb)T B\u22121(x \u2212 xb) and Jo = (1/2)(H(x) \u2212 y)T R\u22121(x \u2212 y). In these expressions, x is the control vector (the model initial state), xb is the background, y the vector of observations and H is the observation operator which computes the model equivalent of the observations from the model state. The matrices B and R are the background and observation error covariance matrices respectively.",
      "The observation error covariance matrix R is a key element of the assimilation system, since its specification relative to B determines the weight given to the observations. This matrix is diagonal since the observation errors are assumed to be uncorrelated. The standard deviation of the error is prescribed to be 20 ms\u22121 for each travel time, which corresponds to 4% of the reference signal.",
      "This section addresses the sensitivity of the assimilation results to the specification of the background error covariance matrix. We compare the results obtained from four different error models. The first one is the reference case (Bref), described in section 2(c), and is compared to a case where there is no background term in the cost-function (B = \u221e). The third case uses an error variance which is proportional to the variance of the reference field (Bprop). The last one is a simple diagonal matrix Bdiag = \u03c32bI, where \u03c32b is the mean value of the diagonal terms of Bref.",
      "Figure 10(a) presents the evolution of the rms error in streamfunction obtained with the four different background error covariance matrices. The assimilation is obviously more efficient when a background term is used. The three experiments with a background term show a similar evolution of the rms error, but the best result is obtained with the Bref matrix."
    ],
    "justification": "The paper uses a variational data assimilation method, which formally incorporates uncertainty through prescribed background (B) and observation (R) error covariance matrices. This goes beyond simple heuristic error bars (Level 1). The authors do not derive a full posterior distribution for the state (which would be Level 3). Instead, they explicitly conduct a series of sensitivity analyses to assess the impact of different specifications of the background error covariance matrix on the assimilation results (e.g., by comparing four different error models). This use of sensitivity analysis to understand how assumptions about error affect the outcome is a clear example of a Level 2 approach to uncertainty quantification.",
