      "The crossover differences are modelled by a set of parameters representing time-tagged orbit corrections, instrumental drift, biases and time-variable sea surface effects. The parameters are estimated by a least squares adjustment.",
      "A unified analysis of all altimeter data from different missions and periods is generally done by a least squares adjustment where the parameters represent a long-term mean sea surface, time variable components and mission-specific system parameters.",
      "For the global gravity field determination satellite altimetry is combined with all other available gravity data, such as terrestrial and air-borne gravity measurements, and observations from dedicated satellite gravity missions. The combination is done by a global least squares adjustment, where the gravity field is represented by a series of spherical harmonic base functions and the coefficients of this series are the unknown parameters to be estimated."
    ],
    "justification": "The paper consistently describes the use of global least-squares adjustment to combine diverse observations (satellite altimetry, terrestrial gravity) with physical models (e.g., orbital models, spherical harmonic representations of the gravity field). This method solves for a single, globally consistent set of model parameters by minimizing the misfit to all data simultaneously in a batch process. This approach, where various data sources and model physics are mathematically combined within a single cost function to produce an optimal state estimate, is a form of synthesis. Data and the model are mathematically inseparable in the adjustment, which aligns with the description of a Level 3 data integration approach.",
