    "evidence_level": 2,
    "evidence_passages": [
      "The verification of altimeter data quality is done by calibration and validation activities. Calibration aims at the detection and quantification of systematic errors in the altimeter measurements or in the corrections applied to the data. This is usually done by comparing the altimeter measurements with in-situ measurements of a well known reference. Validation is the process of error assessment. It is done by analyzing the data itself, e.g. by analyzing data at the intersection of ascending and descending tracks (crossover analysis), and by comparing the data with independent data of the same kind.",
      "A powerful tool for data validation is the analysis of crossover differences. At the intersection of an ascending and a descending ground track the sea surface height should be identical, if the sea surface would be stationary. Thus, any difference indicates inconsistencies in the measurements. Crossover differences are mainly caused by orbit errors.",
      "Global marine gravity models are usually given by a set of spherical harmonic coefficients. These models are derived by combining satellite altimetry with other data, such as ship gravity data or recently also airborne gravity data. The quality of such a model is assessed by comparing it with independent data, e.g. with ship gravity data not used for the model generation."
    ],
    "justification": "The paper describes systematic procedures for verifying data and model quality, which implies verification of the code that performs the processing. Specifically, it mentions \"crossover analysis,\" which is a structured internal consistency check of the processing chain by comparing results at the intersection of satellite tracks. It also describes the practice of assessing final products, like global marine gravity models, by comparing them against independent datasets (e.g., ship-gravity data) not used in their creation. These methods represent structured, system-level tests and comparisons to benchmarks, which align with the Level 2 criteria. The evidence does not rise to Level 3, as there is no mention of specific algorithmic tests like adjoint or Taylor tests.",
