    "dimension": "physics_conservation",
    "has_evidence": true,
    "evidence_level": 3,
    "evidence_passages": [
      "The degree-1 gravity coefficients, representing the motion of the geocenter (the center of mass of the whole Earth system, including the solid Earth, oceans, and atmosphere) with respect to the center of figure (the origin of the terrestrial reference frame), are not directly observable from satellite tracking data [Chao et al., 2000]. However, GRACE observations of mass redistribution can be used to compute the associated geocenter motion under the assumption of mass conservation of the surface fluid layer (atmosphere, oceans, and continental water).",
      "The total mass change within the surface layer (atmosphere, oceans, and land) will cause a uniform change in the height of the global mean sea level, which is related to the degree-0 gravity change and cannot be determined from GRACE gravity measurements. In this study, we assume the total mass of the surface fluid layer is conserved, and remove the spatial mean from the surface mass change at each epoch."
    ],
    "justification": "The paper explicitly states that it calculates geocenter motion (degree-1 gravity coefficients) under the strict 'assumption of mass conservation of the surface fluid layer'. It further clarifies this by stating, 'we assume the total mass of the surface fluid layer is conserved, and remove the spatial mean from the surface mass change at each epoch.' This is not merely monitoring a budget; it is the enforcement of a strict physical conservation law (a closed budget) as a necessary constraint to derive a physical quantity that is otherwise unobservable by the instrument. This direct application and enforcement of a closed budget aligns with the criteria for Level 3.",
    "paper_doi": "10.1029/2004GL021670",
    "paper_title": "Low degree gravitational changes from GRACE: Validation and interpretation"
  },
