      "Figure 1 compares the GRACE and SLR C20 time series. Both show very similar annual variations, with comparable amplitudes and phases. The weighted root-mean-square (WRMS) difference between the two is 1.2 x 10-10, which is comparable to the estimated uncertainty of monthly SLR C20 estimates (about 1.0 x 10-10).",
      "Figure 3c compares GRACE observed ocean mass change with the ECCO model prediction. ... The correlation between the two is 0.81. The RMS difference is 2.1 x 10^15 kg, equivalent to about 0.6 cm of sea level change, which is at the same level as the estimated uncertainty in the ECCO model prediction."
    ],
    "justification": "The paper quantifies uncertainty by analyzing the spread of results. This is done in two main ways: 1) by calculating the standard deviation of a time series of monthly solutions, treating the temporal sequence as an ensemble of measurements, and 2) by computing the root-mean-square (RMS) difference between GRACE results and independent measurements from other sources (e.g., SLR, ocean models). Using the spread between different datasets or the temporal variability of a single dataset as a proxy for error is characteristic of a Level 2 (Ensemble) approach.",
