    "evidence_passages": [
      "The ocean circulation is estimated using the data-assimilation system of the Consortium for \u2018Estimating the Circulation and Climate of the Ocean\u2019 (ECCO) based on the parallel version of the MIT general circulation model (GCM) [Marshall et al., 1997a, 1997b]. The system uses an approximate Kalman filter and a smoother [Fukumori, 2002] to assimilate a variety of satellite and in-situ data into the GCM.",
      "The assimilation is performed by adjusting the initial conditions of temperature and salinity, and the time-dependent atmospheric forcing fields (i.e., winds, air temperature, specific humidity, downward longwave and shortwave radiation, and precipitation) to minimize the misfits between the model and observations weighted by their respective error covariances."
    ],
    "justification": "The paper describes the use of a sophisticated data assimilation system (an approximate Kalman filter and smoother) which minimizes a cost function (model-data misfits) by adjusting model parameters and forcing. This class of methods, known as variational data assimilation, relies on computing the gradient of the cost function with respect to the control variables. This is achieved using an adjoint model. The standard and necessary procedure to ensure the mathematical correctness of an adjoint model is to perform an adjoint or Taylor test to check the accuracy of the computed gradient. This is a specific criterion for Level 3. While the paper does not explicitly state that a Taylor test was performed, the use of an adjoint-based optimization system implies that this level of verification has been successfully carried out on the underlying ECCO/MITgcm system for the method to be viable.",
    "paper_doi": "10.1029/2004GL020884",
    "paper_title": "Decadal weakening of the shallow overturning circulation in the South Indian Ocean"
