    "evidence_passages": [
      "The simplest model for diurnal SST variation is based on the one-dimensional heat budget in the surface mixed layer. Assuming that the surface mixed layer has a uniform temperature (Ts) and a constant depth (H), the heat budget is written as: \u03c1_w c_p H dT_s/dt = Q_net - Q_pen, where \u03c1_w is the density of sea water, c_p is the specific heat of sea water, t is time, Q_net is the net heat flux at the sea surface (the sum of net shortwave radiation, net longwave radiation, latent heat flux and sensible heat flux), and Q_pen is the solar radiation penetrating through the bottom of the surface mixed layer.",
      "More sophisticated models have been also developed, in which the vertical profile of temperature is calculated by solving the one-dimensional heat diffusion equation with a vertically variable thermal diffusivity, which is determined by a turbulence closure model (e.g., Mellor and Yamada 1982). Such models are referred to as turbulence closure models or mixed layer models. These models can represent the diurnal variation of mixed layer depth as well as that of SST.",
      "Wada (2005b) embedded the PWP model (Price et al. 1986) into an OGCM and performed a simulation of the North Pacific. The PWP model was forced with 3-hourly surface fluxes from an atmospheric reanalysis data set."
    ],
    "justification": "The paper reviews various models used to simulate diurnal sea surface temperature (SST) variation. The foundational principle of these models is the one-dimensional heat budget, a direct application of the law of conservation of energy. This is explicitly stated in the first quote. The second quote describes more advanced models that solve the heat diffusion equation using turbulence closure schemes, indicating the presence of primary, established physics. The third quote shows the application of these physics-based models (like the PWP model) within larger Ocean General Circulation Models (OGCMs). This approach, where primary physical laws are represented and budgets are monitored (e.g., via heat fluxes), but not necessarily with the strict, cross-scale consistency of adjoint or finite element methods, aligns well with Level 2 criteria. The use of parameterizations and coupling schemes is characteristic of this level, as opposed to the empirical nature of Level 1 or the strictly closed budgets of Level 3.",
