      "Sea surface salinity (SSS) is restored to climatological values (Levitus et al., 1994) on a timescale of 30 days.",
      "Without SSS restoring, the model SSS drifts to unrealistic values, a common problem in OGCMs which are typically forced by a combination of reanalysis products and climatologies that may not be fully consistent."
    ],
    "justification": "The paper states that sea surface salinity (SSS) is restored to climatological values. This 'restoring' or 'nudging' is an empirical correction applied to the model to prevent drift. It represents an artificial source or sink of freshwater, meaning the model's freshwater budget does not close based on the supplied physical fluxes alone. This use of 'nudged' physics, where budgets do not close, is a key characteristic of Level 1.",
    "paper_doi": "10.1029/2007JC004096",
    "paper_title": "Mechanisms for recent warming of the North Atlantic: Insights gained with an eddy-permitting model"
