    "dimension": "data_integration",
    "has_evidence": true,
    "evidence_level": 1,
    "evidence_passages": [
      "We use the OCCAM eddy\u2010permitting global ocean model, run for 46 years (1960\u20132005) under forcing from the NCEP/NCAR reanalysis [Kalnay et al., 1996].",
      "Surface boundary conditions are based on daily mean NCEP/NCAR reanalysis fields, from which we derive surface fluxes.",
      "In addition, sea surface salinity (SSS) is restored to monthly mean climatological values from Levitus et al. [1994], with a piston velocity of 50 m (30 d)\u22121 (equivalent to a restoring timescale of 30 days for a 50 m deep mixed layer)."
    ],
    "justification": "The paper describes a model experiment that is explicitly \"forced\" by atmospheric reanalysis data (NCEP/NCAR) to determine its surface fluxes. Furthermore, a non-physical restoring term is applied to the sea surface salinity, forcing it towards a climatological dataset. This technique, also known as nudging, is a clear example of a Level 1 (Forced) approach, where the model is driven by data and its own physics (in this case, salt conservation at the surface) can be violated to conform to observations. There is no mention of sequential or synthesis-based data assimilation methods.",
    "paper_doi": "10.1029/2007JC004096",
    "paper_title": "Mechanisms for recent warming of the North Atlantic: Insights gained with an eddy-permitting model"
  },
  {
    "dimension": "verification",
    "has_evidence": true,
    "evidence_level": 1,
    "evidence_passages": [
      "The model is spun-up from rest, initialized with climatological temperature and salinity (from the World Ocean Atlas 2001 [Stephens et al., 2002; Conkright et al., 2002]) over the period 1960\u20131979, with surface forcing from the \u2018normal-year\u2019 Common Ocean-ice Reference Experiments (CORE) data set [Large and Yeager, 2004]. The 20-year spin-up is found to be sufficient for most of the upper ocean to adjust to a repeating seasonal cycle, with drift of less than 0.01\u00b0C per decade in areally averaged SST. For the deep ocean, the spin-up is continued for a further 40 years, with the same repeated annual cycle forcing. The deep ocean state after this extended spin-up is close to a steady state, with a small residual drift, and the interannual run is initialized from this state. The model is then integrated from 1980 to 2004, subject to interannually varying surface forcing from the CORE data set, which provides a consistent set of air-sea fluxes and associated atmospheric state variables, based on NCEP-NCAR reanalysis and satellite observations."
    ],
    "justification": "The paper describes a multi-decade model spin-up followed by a 25-year experiment. The description of the model reaching a stable, quasi-equilibrium state (\"close to a steady state, with a small residual drift\") and the successful completion of the subsequent long integration from which results are presented, demonstrates that the code is functional and stable. This directly supports the Level 1 criterion that the 'Code runs' without crashing. No evidence is provided for higher levels of verification, such as unit tests, convergence studies (Level 2), or comparisons to exact benchmarks (Level 3).",
    "paper_doi": "10.1029/2007JC004096",
    "paper_title": "Mechanisms for recent warming of the North Atlantic: Insights gained with an eddy-permitting model"
  },
  {
    "dimension": "validation",
    "has_evidence": true,
    "evidence_level": 2,
    "evidence_passages": [
      "Correlations between modeled and observed SST anomalies are generally high (>0.7) over much of the basin, particularly in the subtropical gyre and the subpolar North Atlantic where the NAO influence is strongest.",
      "The model\u2019s NAO index, derived from sea level pressure (SLP) fields from the NCEP forcing, is highly correlated (r = 0.97) with the station-based index of Hurrell [1995] (Figure 6).",
      "Time series of upper ocean (0\u2013700 m) heat content anomalies for the North Atlantic (Figure 7) show that the model reproduces the observed warming trend from the mid-1990s onward, although the magnitude of the model warming is somewhat larger than observed. The correlation between the two time series is 0.81.",
      "In the annual mean, model SST is typically biased warm by <1\u00b0C across much of the subtropical and subpolar gyres... Colder biases of similar magnitude are found in the eastern subtropical gyre, in the vicinity of the Canary Current, and on the Newfoundland Shelf."
    ],
    "justification": "The paper includes a dedicated validation section (Section 3) that compares model output against a range of observational datasets (HadISST, Hurrell NAO index, Levitus heat content, climatologies). The authors move beyond qualitative, Level 1 comparisons by reporting specific statistical metrics. They provide correlation coefficients for key climate indices and variables, such as the NAO index (r=0.97) and upper ocean heat content anomalies (r=0.81). They also quantify regional biases in sea surface temperature (e.g., \"biased warm by <1\u00b0C\"). This use of statistical metrics like correlation and quantified bias to assess model performance against real-world data directly meets the criteria for Level 2. The validation uses independent datasets but is not presented as a blind, process-level validation required for Level 3.",
    "paper_doi": "10.1029/2007JC004096",
    "paper_title": "Mechanisms for recent warming of the North Atlantic: Insights gained with an eddy-permitting model"
  },
  {
    "dimension": "uncertainty_quantification",
    "has_evidence": true,
    "evidence_level": 2,
    "evidence_passages": [
      "The use of a single eddy-permitting integration limits the present analysis. To gain some appreciation of the sensitivity of our findings to model physics, we have additionally considered two integrations of a non-eddy-permitting configuration of the same model (with 2\u00b0 resolution and 46 vertical levels).",
      "Both integrations are forced by daily NCEP-NCAR reanalysis fields [Kalnay et al., 1996] over 1958\u20132001... one integration (hereafter NCEP) is configured with the same parameterizations as ORCA025-G70... The second integration (hereafter NCEP-G) is configured with the Gent and McWilliams [1990] parameterization of sub-grid-scale eddy-induced tracer advection...",
      "The pattern of OHC trends is broadly similar in all three integrations (Figure 10), providing some confidence in the robustness of the spatial pattern of warming identified with ORCA025-G70. However, the vertical profile of warming differs considerably between the eddy-permitting and non-eddy-permitting integrations (Figure 11)."
    ],
    "justification": "The authors acknowledge the limitation of using a single model run and conduct a sensitivity analysis to address this. They compare their primary results with those from two additional model integrations that use a different resolution, different atmospheric forcing data (NCEP-NCAR vs. ERA-40), and different parameterizations (one with Gent and McWilliams). By comparing the results from this small ensemble of three runs, they assess the robustness of their findings to changes in model physics and forcing. This approach of using a spread of runs as a proxy for uncertainty and to build confidence in the results is characteristic of a Level 2 (Ensemble) approach to uncertainty quantification.",
    "paper_doi": "10.1029/2007JC004096",
    "paper_title": "Mechanisms for recent warming of the North Atlantic: Insights gained with an eddy-permitting model"
  },
  {
    "dimension": "numerical_fidelity",
    "has_evidence": true,
