      "Discontinuous Galerkin (DG) finite element methods satisfy a number of these requirements: they are locally conservative, can easily handle complex geometries and unstructured meshes, and the order of accuracy can be easily changed.",
      "An important property of the DG scheme is that it is locally conservative. This can be seen by summing equation (6) over all elements T \u2208 T_h... Since the numerical flux h is single valued on interior edges, the edge integrals cancel out for each pair of adjacent elements, i.e. \u222b_e [h \u00b7 n] dS = 0. We are then left with the global conservation law...",
      "The limiter must be constructed such that it is conservative.",
      "Figure 3: L2 error and total mass for the solid body rotation test case. (The plot for total mass shows a perfectly horizontal line at 1.0, indicating zero change/loss over time)."
    ],
    "justification": "The paper is centered on a Discontinuous Galerkin (DG) finite element method, which is explicitly selected for being 'locally conservative'. The authors provide a mathematical derivation showing that local conservation on each element guarantees global conservation for the entire domain due to the formulation of numerical fluxes at element interfaces. This is a hallmark of a numerically consistent, high-fidelity scheme. Even when applying modifications to the solution (a slope limiter to prevent non-physical oscillations), it is explicitly stated that 'The limiter must be constructed such that it is conservative.' Finally, the results section includes a plot for a standard test case showing that the total mass is perfectly conserved throughout the simulation. This demonstrates mathematically and empirically that budgets are strictly closed, which directly aligns with the Level 3 criteria.",
