      "For the purpose of verification a manufactured solution is commonly used. We choose the following solution to verify our code: u(x, y, t) = sin(\u03c0x) sin(\u03c0y) cos(t). By plugging this into the PDE (2.12) we obtain a source term f(x, y, t). Our DG code is then used to solve the modified PDE and the solution is compared to the manufactured solution.",
      "To verify the code, we first determine the order of accuracy of the spatial discretisation. ... The order of accuracy p is then computed by p \u2248 log(E1/E2) / log(h1/h2) where E1 and E2 are the errors for grid spacings h1 and h2, respectively. In Figure 4.1 we plot the L2 error of the solution versus the number of elements N for different polynomial orders. The order of accuracy is given by the slope of the lines. We see that the theoretical orders of accuracy of p + 1 are achieved.",
