    "evidence_passages": [
      "The forcing protocol includes a weak restoring of sea surface salinity (SSS) to climatological values... The restoring term acts as a negative feedback to damp spurious model drift in SSS, with the drift arising from imbalances in the prescribed freshwater forcing as well as from model errors. Such a term is non-physical...",
      "The freshwater flux associated with this SSS restoring should be diagnosed and reported, as it provides a useful metric for assessing the model\u2019s freshwater budget.",
      "There is no restoring of sea surface temperature (SST) to observations in CORE-I... This choice allows for the ocean heat budget to be closed, thus enabling a physically meaningful analysis of heat uptake and transport in the simulated ocean.",
      "A fundamental aspect of the CORE-I protocol is its use of realistic freshwater fluxes from river runoff and iceberg calving. We thus do not employ virtual salt fluxes to mimic freshwater fluxes. In this way, ocean volume and mass are conserved."
    ],
    "justification": "The paper describes the CORE protocol, which explicitly includes a non-physical 'leak' in the system: a weak restoring of sea surface salinity (SSS) to climatology. This immediately disqualifies it from Level 3 (Strictly Closed Budgets). However, the protocol is a step above Level 1 because it explicitly requires that this non-physical freshwater flux be 'diagnosed and reported'. This aligns perfectly with the Level 2 criteria of 'global budgets monitored but not strictly enforced'. Furthermore, the authors deliberately avoid a similar restoring for sea surface temperature (SST) for the explicit purpose of allowing 'the ocean heat budget to be closed'. This demonstrates a clear awareness and monitoring of global budgets, even if one budget (freshwater) is not strictly closed for pragmatic reasons (to control model drift).",
    "paper_doi": "10.1016/J.OCEMOD.2008.08.007",
    "paper_title": "Coordinated Ocean-ice Reference Experiments (COREs)"
  },
