      "The protocol for the interannual experiments is to run for five cycles of the 1958\u20132000 forcing fields, with the expectation that the solution drift is small by the fifth cycle. We recommend monitoring global average quantities to diagnose the approach to equilibrium.",
      "This figure [Figure 4] provides a useful diagnostic to assess model drift, with some models showing a steady drift even after 200 years of forcing, whereas others have equilibrated."
    ],
    "justification": "The paper describes the Coordinated Ocean-ice Reference Experiments (COREs) protocol, which serves as a structured test for global ocean-ice models. The protocol requires long-term simulations (multiple centuries) and explicitly recommends 'monitoring global average quantities to diagnose the approach to equilibrium' and assess model drift. This is exemplified by figures analyzing global mean sea surface salinity drift and temperature over the simulation period. This practice of monitoring integrated quantities for non-physical drifts (e.g., lack of conservation) over long runs is a form of structured, whole-model testing that goes beyond merely functional code (Level 1). It is a standard method in climate modeling to verify the stability and conservative properties of a model's numerical implementation, fitting the 'Structured' criteria of Level 2. The paper does not provide evidence of more rigorous algorithmic verification, such as Taylor tests or comparisons to exact benchmarks (Level 3).",
    "paper_doi": "10.1016/J.OCEMOD.2008.08.007",
