    "evidence_passages": [
      "The determination of the time-variable part of the gravity field from SLR data is based on the analysis of the orbital motion of geodetic satellites. This motion is described by a dynamical system whose parameters include, amongst others, the Stokes coefficients of the Earth\u2019s gravity field.",
      "For the non-gravitational forces, we use the new models recommended by the IERS Conventions 2003 [McCarthy and Petit, 2004]: the solar radiation pressure (with the satellite seen as a sphere), the Earth\u2019s albedo and infrared radiation, and the atmospheric drag.",
      "The relativistic effects are taken into account, as well as the gravitational attractions of the Sun, the Moon, and the planets (Venus, Mars, Jupiter, and Saturn).",
      "The luni-solar solid Earth tides are computed following the IERS Conventions 2003, with a frequency-dependent model. The ocean tides are taken into account thanks to the FES2004 model [Lyard et al., 2006]. The pole tide (solid Earth and ocean) is also modeled."
    ],
    "justification": "The paper's entire methodology for deriving gravity field variations relies on a detailed physical model of satellite orbital mechanics. The evidence shows that the model is a 'dynamical system' that incorporates a wide range of primary physical forces, including Earth's gravity, gravitational attractions from the Sun, Moon, and planets, non-gravitational forces like solar radiation pressure and atmospheric drag, and relativistic effects. This comprehensive inclusion of physical laws satisfies the 'Primary physics present' criterion for Level 2. The purpose of the model is to infer changes in the Earth's mass distribution, which is a form of monitoring a global budget (mass). However, the technique is an inversion of observational data and does not enforce a strictly closed mass budget for the Earth system itself, which distinguishes it from Level 3.",
    "paper_doi": "None",
    "paper_title": "Temporal variations of the Earth\u201fs gravity field derived from SLR data over a long period of time"
  },
  {
    "dimension": "data_integration",
    "has_evidence": true,
    "evidence_level": 3,
    "evidence_passages": [
      "The methodology used to derive the gravity field solutions is based on the inversion of a system of normal equations.",
      "The gravity field solutions presented in this paper are computed on a monthly basis, from 1985 to the end of 2008.",
      "The main steps of our procedure are the following one: for each satellite and each month, a precise orbit determination is performed over the monthly arc. In that process, we adjust a certain number of parameters which enables us to reduce the observation residuals (observed SLR measurements minus the computed ones). This is realized through a least-squares fit.",
      "The normal equations of all the solved-for parameters are created at the end of this step. It represents the contribution of one satellite over one month. The last step is the combination of all these individual normal equations, month per month, to solve for the geopotential coefficients only."
    ],
    "justification": "The paper describes a batch least-squares adjustment method performed over monthly data arcs. Within each monthly arc, a precise orbit is determined by fitting a physical model of orbital dynamics to all available Satellite Laser Ranging (SLR) observations simultaneously. This process, described as a \"least-squares fit\" that adjusts model parameters (including the gravity field) to minimize observation residuals over the entire arc, is a form of variational data assimilation. It seeks a single optimal model trajectory that is consistent with both the laws of physics and the full set of observations over the time window. This aligns with the Level 3 description of \"Synthesis\" where \"Data and physics [are] mathematically inseparable\". While the solutions are produced sequentially on a \"monthly basis\", the core data integration technique within each batch is a holistic synthesis over a data arc, which is a standard approach in geodesy analogous to 4D-Var, and not a simple sequential update like a Kalman Filter (Level 2).",
    "paper_doi": "None",
    "paper_title": "Temporal variations of the Earth\u201fs gravity field derived from SLR data over a long period of time"
