      "In this study we use the CAM3 atmospheric general circulation model (AGCM), which has a horizontal resolution of T42 and 26 vertical levels (Collins et al., 2004).",
      "The total atmospheric energy transport, AET, is calculated by vertically integrating the sum of the dry static energy, c p T + gz, and latent heat, Lq, and then zonally integrating the meridional wind component, v.",
      "The atmospheric energy transport (AET) can be divided into a dry static (DSET) and a latent heat (LH) component, AET=DSET+LH, where the former can be further divided into contributions from the time-mean circulation and transient eddies, DSET = DSETmean + DSETeddy. The decomposition of the energy transport is performed as in Lucarini and Fraedrich (2009) and Lucarini et al. (2010)."
    ],
    "justification": "The paper uses the CAM3 atmospheric general circulation model (AGCM), which is founded on fundamental physical principles (e.g., fluid dynamics, thermodynamics). The core of the analysis is an examination of the atmospheric energy transport (AET) and its constituent components (dry static energy, latent heat, mean circulation, transient eddies). This demonstrates that primary physical laws are represented and that the model's energy budget is being explicitly monitored and analyzed. This aligns with the Level 2 criteria of 'Primary physics present; global budgets monitored'. There is insufficient evidence to claim Level 3, as the paper does not discuss the strictness of budget closure or advanced numerical methods like adjoints.",
