    "evidence_passages": [
      "We also use a simple model of the ocean response to wind forcing. The time-varying height of a dome of water h at the centre of a gyre of radius r is given by the Sverdrup relation as dh/dt = (1/\u03c1f) curl(\u03c4) \u2212 (rE/2H)h where \u03c4 is the wind-stress vector, \u03c1 is the water density, f is the Coriolis parameter, H is the depth of the gyre and E is the Ekman number.",
      "We drive the model using the monthly mean NCEP/NCAR wind-stress curl averaged over the Beaufort Gyre region (70.5\u201380.5\u25e6 N, 130\u2013170\u25e6 W). We use the model to determine whether the observed changes in DOT can be explained by the wind forcing alone.",
      "The simple model of the ocean response to the wind forcing reproduces the observed trend in DOT, and much of the interannual variability (Fig. 4)."
    ],
    "justification": "The paper uses a simple, one-and-a-half-layer, baroclinic model to test a hypothesis. This model is 'driven' or 'forced' by wind-stress curl data from the NCEP/NCAR reanalysis. The model's output is then compared to the independently derived observations of Dynamic Ocean Topography (DOT) to see if the model can explain the observations. There is no indication of any data assimilation technique (like a Kalman Filter or 4D-Var) where the observations are used to correct or constrain the model state during its run. The flow of information is one-way: forcing data drives the model, and the result is compared with observations. This corresponds to a Level 1 'Forced' integration, where the model is driven by data.",
