  {
    "dimension": "verification",
    "has_evidence": true,
    "evidence_level": 2,
    "evidence_passages": [
      "For validation, we compare our altimeter-derived DOT with that derived from upward-looking sonar (ULS) and CTD data from three moorings deployed in the Beaufort Gyre by the Woods Hole Oceanographic Institution (WHOI)... Figure 2 shows the altimeter DOT compared with the mooring DOT at the three locations. The root-mean-square (r.m.s.) difference between the altimeter and mooring time series is between 0.03 m and 0.04 m for the three sites, which is well within the combined error of the two data sets (0.15 m for the altimeter and 0.03 m for the moorings)."
    ],
    "justification": "The authors test the output of their entire data processing pipeline, which includes a new algorithm, by comparing the derived Dynamic Ocean Topography (DOT) against independent, in-situ measurements from moorings. They quantify the difference (r.m.s. difference) and show it is within the expected error bounds. This comparison against an established, independent data source serves as a structured, system-level test of the computational method's correctness and accuracy, which aligns with the Level 2 criteria of 'Structured: Unit/Regression tests'.",
