  {
    "dimension": "uncertainty_quantification",
    "has_evidence": true,
    "evidence_level": 2,
    "evidence_passages": [
      "We estimate the total random error in our SSH measurements from the r.m.s. of the differences between SSH values where the ground tracks of the two satellites cross. The ground tracks of ERS-2 and Envisat are near-identical, but offset in time, so crossovers occur where the ascending and descending tracks of the same satellite cross, and these are limited to latitudes below 81.5\u25e6 N. In contrast, ICESat has a different orbit and so it crosses the ERS-2/Envisat tracks over the entire region. The r.m.s. difference is 7.1 cm, which we take as the total random error on an individual measurement.",
      "We calculate the uncertainty in the FWCA by adding in quadrature the errors due to SSH, climatological salinity and the residual error from the linear fit that relates the dynamic ocean height to the FWCA.",
      "The uncertainty in the FWCA from the SSH error alone is 0.18 m, obtained by propagating the 7.1 cm SSH error through the linear fit shown in Fig. 1b. The uncertainty due to the climatological salinity is 0.10 m, which is the standard deviation of the annual mean FWCA calculated from the climatology for the period 2003\u20132008. The residual error from the linear fit is 0.19 m, the r.m.s. of the difference between the hydrographic FWCA and the linear fit. The total error on the annual average FWCA is therefore \u221a(0.18^2 + 0.10^2 + 0.19^2) = 0.28 m. The error in the total FWC anomaly is then 0.28 \u00d7 A_BG, where A_BG is the area of the Beaufort Gyre, which gives an uncertainty of 1,000 km^3."
    ],
    "justification": "The paper employs a formal, frequentist approach to uncertainty quantification. It estimates the random error in the primary satellite measurements by calculating the root-mean-square (r.m.s.) difference at satellite track crossover points. It then identifies and quantifies distinct sources of uncertainty (SSH measurement error, climatological salinity, linear fit residuals) and propagates them using a standard quadrature sum (root sum of squares) to determine the total uncertainty in the final result. This systematic analysis and composition of different error sources is a form of error budget analysis, which aligns with the \"sensitivity analysis\" aspect of Level 2. It is significantly more rigorous than a simple heuristic (Level 1) but does not use a formal Bayesian framework to derive posterior distributions (Level 3).",
