    "evidence_level": 2,
    "evidence_passages": [
      "The Forecasting Ocean Assimilation Model (FOAM) is an operational system run by the UK Met Office. The model is NEMO (the ORCA025 configuration at 1/4\u00b0 resolution), but this implementation includes assimilation of sea surface temperature (SST), sea surface height (SSH) from altimeters, and in situ temperature and salinity profiles from ARGO floats, XBTs and CTDs. The assimilation system is based on a 3-D Var analysis scheme, using the background error covariance statistics from an ensemble of model runs, with a 24-h assimilation cycle (Martin et al., 2007).",
      "The Simple Ocean Data Assimilation (SODA) reanalysis (Carton and Giese, 2008) uses the POP ocean model, again at 1/4\u00b0 resolution, with sequential assimilation of hydrographic profiles, SST, sea ice and altimeter data."
    ],
    "justification": "The paper describes two models, FOAM and SODA, that explicitly use sequential data assimilation. FOAM is described as using a \"3-D Var analysis scheme\" with a 24-hour cycle, and SODA is described as using \"sequential assimilation\". These methods involve periodic updates to the model state based on observations, which directly corresponds to the Level 2 (Medium) criteria.",
    "paper_doi": "10.1016/J.OCEMOD.2012.12.011",
    "paper_title": "Mozambique Channel eddies in GCMs: A question of resolution and slippage"
  },
  {
    "dimension": "verification",
    "has_evidence": true,
    "evidence_level": 2,
    "evidence_passages": [
      "The two models used in this study are both global configurations of the NEMO (Nucleus for European Modelling of the Ocean) GCM (Madec, 2008). The main configuration used is ORCA025, a 1/4\u00b0 eddy-permitting model, covering the period 1958\u20132007. This forms part of the DRAKKAR consortium reference simulations (The DRAKKAR Group, 2007). The other configuration is ORCA12, a 1/12\u00b0 eddy-resolving model, spanning 1989\u20132008.",
      "Here we use two different resolution global ocean GCMs to examine how well they reproduce the eddies observed in altimetry.",
      "Fig. 6 shows the eddy kinetic energy (EKE) for the three products (observations, ORCA025 and ORCA12) calculated for the period 1993\u20132007. The 1/4\u00b0 model has much weaker EKE than the observations, whilst the 1/12\u00b0 is of comparable magnitude."
    ],
    "justification": "The paper performs a resolution study by systematically comparing the outputs of the same model (NEMO) run at two different resolutions: 1/4\u00b0 (ORCA025) and 1/12\u00b0 (ORCA12). This investigation into how the solution changes with grid refinement is a form of a convergence study, which is a criterion for Level 2. Although the ultimate comparison is against observational data (validation), the structured inter-comparison of model resolutions provides evidence of verification practices aimed at understanding the model's numerical behavior.",
    "paper_doi": "10.1016/J.OCEMOD.2012.12.011",
    "paper_title": "Mozambique Channel eddies in GCMs: A question of resolution and slippage"
  },
  {
    "dimension": "validation",
    "has_evidence": true,
    "evidence_level": 2,
    "evidence_passages": [
      "Fig. 1 shows the tracks of long-lived eddies (lifetime >90 days) for the period 2002\u20132006 for the AVISO altimetry dataset and the four models. There is a general similarity between all plots... For the higher resolution models (ORCA12 and FOAM12), there is a good visual correspondence with the altimetry record, with both models showing a similar density of tracks and a high concentration of eddy genesis in the narrowest part of the Channel (\u223c15\u00b0S).",
      "Table 1 gives the basic statistics on the number and properties of eddies detected in the different datasets. The AVISO product has on average 4.2 long-lived AC eddies and 4.6 long-lived C eddies present at any one time in the region 10\u201325\u00b0S, 35\u201345\u00b0E. ORCA12 produces 20% more AC eddies and 10% fewer C eddies than observed, but the general correspondence is quite good.",
      "The mean eddy propagation speeds are also given in Table 1. The altimetry-derived values are 7.5 and 6.6 km/day for AC and C eddies respectively. The non-assimilative models have mean speeds that are 30\u201350% too low, whilst the FOAM products give speeds very similar to those observed.",
      "Fig. 2 shows the distribution of eddy radii for the AVISO dataset and the four models. The observed anticyclonic (AC) and cyclonic (C) eddies have median radii of 95 and 85 km respectively. The ORCA12 model has a similar distribution to AVISO, although with a slight shift to smaller radii."
    ],
    "justification": "The paper performs a detailed validation of model-generated ocean eddies against an observational satellite altimetry dataset (AVISO). The analysis goes beyond simple qualitative comparison (Level 1) by providing quantitative statistical metrics. The evidence shows direct statistical comparisons of eddy properties, including the average number of eddies, their mean propagation speeds, and distributions of their radii and amplitudes. For example, the paper quantifies that one model produces '20% more AC eddies' and that other models have speeds that are '30-50% too low' compared to observations. This use of summary statistics and distribution comparisons to quantify model skill aligns with the criteria for Level 2.",
    "paper_doi": "10.1016/J.OCEMOD.2012.12.011",
    "paper_title": "Mozambique Channel eddies in GCMs: A question of resolution and slippage"
