    "evidence_passages": [
      "Inverse modeling has become a widely used tool for determining model parameters and for diagnosing and reducing uncertainties in DGVMs and ecosystem models (Kaminski et al. 2002; Knorr and Heimann 2001; Rayner et al. 2005; Zaehle et al. 2005).",
      "For instance, the Carbon Cycle Data Assimilation System (CCDAS; Rayner et al. 2005) used a variational approach to assimilate CO2 concentration data in a coupled model of the terrestrial biosphere (BETHY) and atmospheric transport (TM2) to optimize parameters of the BETHY model."
    ],
    "justification": "The paper describes the use of advanced data assimilation techniques, specifically mentioning \"inverse modeling\" and a \"variational approach\" (a form of 4D-Var) used in the Carbon Cycle Data Assimilation System (CCDAS). This method mathematically combines observational data (CO2 concentrations) with model logic (biosphere and atmospheric transport models) to find an optimal solution, which is characteristic of a Level 3 synthesis approach where data and physics are inseparable.",
