      "...we applied version 6.0 of TEM (McGuire et al. 2001; Euskirchen et al. 2009)...",
      "To assess potential changes in vegetation distribution in Siberia, we used two bioclimatic models, the Siberian Biome-Climate Model (SiBCliM) (Tchebakova et al. 2009) and a simple model that describes the shift of the northern timberline (SHIFT M) (Kharuk et al. 2006, 2010)."
    ],
    "justification": "The paper provides evidence for Level 1 by mentioning a specific model version number (\"version 6.0 of TEM\"), which indicates an ad-hoc approach to versioning rather than a formal version control system like Git. Furthermore, the primary form of documentation for the models used is through citations to other academic papers (e.g., for SiBCliM and SHIFTM), which constitutes sparse documentation. There is no mention of public repositories, maintenance guides, or community health, which would be required for higher levels.",
