    "justification": "The paper explicitly describes the calculation and use of a 'full error covariance matrix' resulting from a least-squares adjustment. This matrix represents the complete uncertainty information, including variances (standard deviations) and correlations between all estimated parameters. The authors further describe the formal 'error propagation' of this full covariance matrix to derive uncertainties for other quantities (e.g., geoid heights). This use of a covariance matrix for error propagation is a formal, probabilistic method for quantifying and propagating uncertainty, which directly corresponds to a Level 3 rating.",
