    "evidence_passages": [
      "We use the Massachusetts Institute of Technology general circulation model (MITgcm) [Marshall et al., 1997a, 1997b] to simulate an idealized sector of the Southern Ocean. The model solves the hydrostatic Boussinesq primitive equations on an f plane...",
      "In order to quantify the rates of isopycnal mixing and ventilation, we analyze the evolution of a suite of passive tracers... The tracer budget equation is \u2202C/\u2202t + \u2207 \u22c5 (uC) = \u2207 \u22c5 (K\u2207C) + S.",
      "Integrating the tracer equation (2) over the volume V between two isopycnals... and applying the divergence theorem gives... d/dt \u222bV C dV = \u2212 \u222b\u2202V C(u \u2212 w) \u00b7 n dS + \u222b\u2202V K\u2207C \u00b7 n dS + \u222bV S dV. The terms in equation (3) represent (from left to right): the rate of change of tracer mass within the volume, the advective flux across the isopycnal surfaces, the advective flux across the side boundaries of the channel..., the diffusive flux across the isopycnal surfaces, the diffusive flux across the side boundaries, and the surface flux."
    ],
    "justification": "The paper uses the MITgcm, a model built on the primitive equations which embody the conservation of mass, momentum, and energy. The core methodology relies on a strict, term-by-term budget analysis of a passive tracer's conservation equation. The authors explicitly formulate and integrate the tracer conservation law over a control volume, accounting for all fluxes (advective, diffusive) across boundaries and internal sources/sinks. This rigorous application of a closed budget as the central analytical tool is a clear example of 'Strictly Closed Budgets' and full consistency, aligning with the criteria for Level 3.",
    "paper_doi": "10.1002/2015GL066238",
    "paper_title": "Southern Ocean isopycnal mixing and ventilation changes driven by winds"
