    "evidence_passages": [
      "The uncertainty of OHC change is estimated from the standard error of the mean for each year derived from 100 realizations of the mapping method (Cheng et al., 2016a). Cheng et al. (2016a) created 100 realizations of the global temperature field by using different parameters in the mapping method... Then the uncertainty of the OHC trend is obtained from the time series of the standard error using the method of linear trend analysis with autoregressive noise (Santer et al., 2008).",
      "To present a robust result, we first calculate the OHC time series for each individual model run and then calculate the ensemble median and the 5 to 95 % range.",
      "The CMIP5 models show large spread in OHC changes, suggesting that some models are not state-of-the-art and require further improvements. However, the ensemble median has excellent agreement with our observational estimate: 0.68 [0.54\u20130.82]\u202f\u00d7\u202f1022\u202fJ\u202fyr\u22121 (0.42\u202fWm\u22122) from 1970 to 2005 and 1.25 [1.10\u20131.41]\u202f\u00d7\u202f1022\u202fJ\u202fyr\u22121 (0.77\u202fWm\u22122) from 1992 to 2005."
    ],
    "justification": "The paper quantifies uncertainty for both observational estimates and model simulations using ensemble-based methods. For the observational data, uncertainty is derived from an ensemble of 100 realizations created by varying parameters in the mapping method, which is a form of sensitivity analysis. For the model simulations, the paper explicitly uses the spread (5 to 95% range) of a multi-model ensemble (CMIP5) as a proxy for uncertainty. Both of these approaches\u2014sensitivity analysis and using the spread of runs as an error proxy\u2014are characteristic of a Level 2 approach to uncertainty quantification.",
