    "evidence_passages": [
      "We used global, daily estimates of ocean surface currents and winds for the period 1992\u20132011 from the Estimating the Circulation and Climate of the Ocean, Phase II (ECCO2) project, which is a data-assimilative product that is constrained by a full suite of satellite and in situ observations using a Green\u2019s Function approach (Menemenlis et al. 2005, 2008).",
      "A key feature of the ECCO2 project is that the estimates are obtained by adjusting initial conditions, atmospheric forcing fields and model parameters of the MITgcm so as to minimize misfits to the vast number of available ocean observations, while being consistent with the underlying model dynamics. This ensures that the resulting ocean circulation estimates are physically plausible and dynamically self-consistent (i.e. strictly obeying conservation laws of heat, salt, water and momentum)."
    ],
    "justification": "The paper uses ocean circulation and wind data from the ECCO2 project. The methodology of ECCO2 is explicitly described as adjusting model parameters to fit observations while remaining 'consistent with the underlying model dynamics'. Most importantly, the paper states that this process ensures the resulting estimates are 'strictly obeying conservation laws of heat, salt, water and momentum'. This direct statement of strictly closed budgets for multiple physical properties is a clear and unambiguous indicator of Level 3.",
