      "Here, we used a near-global configuration of the Massachusetts Institute of Technology general circulation model (MITgcm; Marshall et al. 1997) that is optimized by Green's functions to a vast collection of satellite and in situ data (ECCO-GODAE, version 3; Wunsch & Heimbach 2007, Menemenlis et al. 2008).",
      "This ECCO-GODAE v3 state estimate provides a physically consistent, time-evolving description of the ocean circulation at a nominal 1\u00b0 horizontal resolution and 50 vertical levels for the period 1992\u20132009 (Menemenlis et al. 2008)."
    ],
    "justification": "The dispersal model described in the paper is driven by ocean current and wind data from the ECCO-GODAE v3 state estimate. This dataset is not raw data, but rather the output of a general circulation model (MITgcm) that has been 'optimized... to a vast collection of satellite and in situ data'. This optimization, which aims to create a 'physically consistent' description of the ocean, is a form of 4D-Var data assimilation (the ECCO group uses an adjoint or Green's functions method). This process makes the model physics and the observational data mathematically inseparable over the assimilation period, which is the definition of Level 3 (Synthesis). The paper's entire methodology relies on this high-level synthesis of data and model physics.",
