  {
    "dimension": "physics_conservation",
    "has_evidence": true,
    "evidence_level": 2,
    "evidence_passages": [
      "A common issue in data assimilation is that the assimilation of observations of state variables can introduce imbalances into the model physics, for instance, a violation of the conservation of mass and energy [Pan and Wood, 2006; Pipunic et al., 2013]. In our study, the assimilation was performed on the water storage states, and the fluxes (ET and R) were not updated in the assimilation step. They were estimated by the model W3RA using the updated states as the initial conditions for the next time step. This means that at the time step of assimilation, the updated change in storage (dS/dt) is not necessarily balanced by the net flux (P-ET-R).",
      "The imbalance can be computed as the residual of the water balance equation (equation (1)), i.e., \u03b5 = dS/dt - (P-ET-R). We found that the imbalance is very small compared to other water balance components. For instance, the standard deviation of the monthly imbalance over the MDB is 0.44 mm/month for the GRACE-only experiment and 0.48 mm/month for the joint assimilation, which are nearly 1% of the standard deviation of monthly precipitation (41.4 mm/month)."
    ],
    "justification": "The paper uses a model based on the primary physics of water balance. The authors explicitly acknowledge that their data assimilation method introduces a \"violation of the conservation of mass,\" creating an imbalance in the water budget. They then monitor this imbalance by calculating the residual of the water balance equation and conclude that it is small. This methodology perfectly aligns with the Level 2 criteria: \"Primary physics present; global budgets monitored but not strictly enforced.\" The budget is not ignored (ruling out Level 1) but it is also not strictly closed (ruling out Level 3).",
    "paper_doi": "10.1002/2016WR019641",
    "paper_title": "Improved water balance component estimates through joint assimilation of GRACE water storage and SMOS soil moisture retrievals"
  },
  {
    "dimension": "data_integration",
    "has_evidence": true,
    "evidence_level": 2,
    "evidence_passages": [
      "The EnKS [Evensen, 2003, 2009] is a variant of the popular Ensemble Kalman Filter (EnKF) [Evensen, 1994, 2003] and uses an ensemble of model integrations to estimate the background error covariance.",
      "The EnKS algorithm is comprised of two steps: a forecast step and an analysis step. In the forecast step, the model state variables are propagated forward in time using the model physics...",
      "In the analysis step, the model states at time k are updated using observations available up to the end of a predefined assimilation window, m, with m >= k."
    ],
    "justification": "The paper employs an Ensemble Kalman Smoother (EnKS), which is an advanced variant of the Ensemble Kalman Filter. The methodology is explicitly described as a sequential process with two distinct steps: a 'forecast step' where the model runs forward, and an 'analysis step' where the model states are updated with observations. This sequential nature, involving periodic updates to the model trajectory, is the defining characteristic of a Level 2 data integration scheme.",
    "paper_doi": "10.1002/2016WR019641",
    "paper_title": "Improved water balance component estimates through joint assimilation of GRACE water storage and SMOS soil moisture retrievals"
  },
  {
    "dimension": "verification",
    "has_evidence": true,
    "evidence_level": 2,
    "evidence_passages": [
      "To evaluate the performance of the data assimilation system and the potential benefit of assimilating GRACE and SMOS data, we conducted a series of synthetic twin experiments. The synthetic experiments were based on the standard OSSE (Observing System Simulation Experiment) method.",
      "First, a \u2018truth\u2019 run was generated by running the W3RA model forward from 1980 to 2014, forced by the AWAP meteorological data set. The model states and fluxes from this run were considered the \u2018true\u2019 water balance components.",
      "Finally, the synthetic observations were assimilated into the W3RA model, which was deliberately forced by a different precipitation data set (MSWEP) to also test the ability of the assimilation to correct for forcing errors. The assimilation results were then compared with the \u2018truth\u2019 run to assess the performance of the EnKS and the potential of the two different observation types to constrain the water balance components."
    ],
    "justification": "The paper describes the use of synthetic twin experiments, also known as an Observing System Simulation Experiment (OSSE). This is a structured test where a known 'truth' is generated by the model, and synthetic observations are created from this truth. The data assimilation system is then evaluated on its ability to recover the known 'truth' by assimilating these synthetic observations. This methodology serves to verify that the assimilation algorithm is implemented correctly and performs as expected under controlled conditions, which directly corresponds to the Level 2 criteria of using structured tests and convergence studies.",
    "paper_doi": "10.1002/2016WR019641",
    "paper_title": "Improved water balance component estimates through joint assimilation of GRACE water storage and SMOS soil moisture retrievals"
  },
