      "In the present study, we attempt to relate the observed land subsidence in the Nile Delta to the different potential driving factors. These are mainly neotectonic activity and anthropogenic activities.",
      "The relationship between land subsidence and groundwater withdrawal is shown by comparing the results of land subsidence with the available groundwater level data for two different locations (Figs. 11, 12). A strong temporal correlation can be observed between the two time series. In general, the land subsidence time series follows the groundwater level time series. In addition, the long-term trend in the land subsidence time series follows the declining trend of the groundwater level.",
      "The high subsidence rates are mostly related to Holocene sediments compaction and anthropogenic activities. The Holocene sediments are characterized by high clay and peat contents, which are known to be highly compressible. In addition, these sediments are not yet fully consolidated. The anthropogenic activities mainly include groundwater and gas extraction."
    ],
    "justification": "The paper uses observational data (InSAR and GPS) to measure subsidence rates. The analysis of the causes of this subsidence is empirical and correlational, not based on a first-principles physical model. The authors identify physical drivers like sediment compaction and groundwater withdrawal and show a correlation between observed subsidence and factors like groundwater levels and sediment type. However, they do not formulate a quantitative physical model that enforces conservation laws (e.g., a mass balance between extracted water and soil compaction volume). The budget of subsidence causes is discussed qualitatively but is not calculated or closed. This corresponds to Level 1: \"Empirical or 'Nudged' physics; budgets do not close or are ignored\".",
    "paper_doi": "10.1007/s12665-018-8001-6",
    "paper_title": "New estimation of Nile Delta subsidence rates from InSAR and GPS analysis"
