    "evidence_passages": [
      "To combine the InSAR results with the GPS velocities, we adopted the method of tying the InSAR results to the reference frame defined by the GPS stations (e.g., Casu et al. 2011; Fuhrmann et al. 2015). We used the 10 permanent GPS stations which are located in the study area as reference points. First, we calculated the differences between the InSAR velocities and the GPS vertical velocities at the locations of the 10 GPS sites.",
      "Then, we modeled these differences by estimating an offset and a planar ramp (tilt) using a least-squares adjustment to minimize the residuals between the InSAR and GPS velocities. The estimated offset and ramp were then subtracted from the entire InSAR velocity field to obtain the corrected velocity map tied to the GPS reference frame.",
      "After applying this correction, we evaluated the differences between the corrected InSAR and GPS velocities at the same 10 GPS stations. We found that the systematic errors are minimized and the differences are randomly distributed with zero mean (Fig. 4). The standard deviation of the residuals between InSAR and GPS velocities at the selected 10 GPS sites is about \u00b1 1.1 mm/year."
    ],
    "justification": "The authors perform a structured test of their InSAR processing results by comparing them against an independent, high-quality dataset (GPS velocities). They use the GPS data as a benchmark to identify and correct for systematic errors (offset and ramp) in the InSAR velocity field through a least-squares adjustment. They then explicitly evaluate the outcome by checking that the residuals are minimized and randomly distributed with a zero mean. This process of calibrating and validating one dataset against another serves as a form of regression test for their processing workflow, which aligns with the 'Structured' criteria for Level 2.",
    "paper_doi": "10.1007/s12665-018-8001-6",
    "paper_title": "New estimation of Nile Delta subsidence rates from InSAR and GPS analysis"
