    "evidence_passages": [
      "To check our hypothesis about the atmospheric control of the near-surface bloom and its evolution to a DCM, we calculated for the two study regions the daily net heat flux (Qnet) at the air-sea interface from 2003 to 2017 using daily data from the Objectively Analyzed air-sea Fluxes (OAFlux) project.",
      "The Qnet is the sum of the net shortwave radiation (Qsw), net longwave radiation (Qlw), latent (Ql), and sensible (Qs) heat fluxes (Qnet = Qsw + Qlw + Qs + Ql). A positive Qnet value means that the ocean is gaining heat from the atmosphere, and a negative value means that it is losing heat.",
      "The MLD was defined as the first depth at which the density value was 0.03 kg m\u22123 greater than the density value at 10 m depth.",
      "To describe the vertical structure of the water column, the Brunt-V\u00e4is\u00e4l\u00e4 frequency (N2) was calculated for each station. N2 is a measure of the water column stability..."
    ],
    "justification": "The paper is an observational and data-analysis study, not a prognostic modeling study. It uses an empirical approach, leveraging satellite, in-situ, and reanalysis data to understand physical drivers of a biological process. It applies physical principles by calculating quantities like the Mixed Layer Depth (MLD) from density profiles and the net air-sea heat flux (Qnet). The calculation of Qnet represents a surface heat budget, but it is assembled diagnostically from various external data products rather than being an enforced, self-consistent budget within a prognostic model. This use of physics to analyze empirical data, where budgets are calculated from external sources rather than being strictly enforced within a closed system, aligns with the 'Empirical... physics' and 'budgets do not close' (in the sense of a self-consistent, enforced constraint) criteria of Level 1.",
