    "justification": "The paper uses standard statistical measures (correlation coefficient R and p-value) to report the significance of the relationship between two variables. This provides a measure of confidence in the finding, but it does not quantify the error bounds on the measurements or model predictions themselves. Furthermore, the paper explicitly acknowledges major sources of uncertainty, such as the choice of thresholds for defining key metrics. However, instead of quantifying this uncertainty through sensitivity analysis (Level 2) or probabilistic methods (Level 3), the authors address it heuristically. They justify their choices by appealing to 'widely used criteria in the scientific literature' and argue for the 'robustness' of the results based on their consistency across different regions. This reliance on established practice and qualitative justification for robustness fits the 'Heuristic' and 'Expert judgment' characterization of Level 1.",
