    "evidence_passages": [
      "While less common in the direct measurement literature, Bayesian inference offers a powerful framework for UQ. It can formally combine prior knowledge with measurement data to produce a posterior probability distribution of the flux, naturally providing a comprehensive characterization of uncertainty. For instance, Bayesian calibration of model parameters using measurement data can propagate parameter uncertainty through to the final flux estimate.",
      "More advanced techniques, such as Monte Carlo (MC) simulations, have been increasingly adopted. MC methods propagate the full probability distributions of input parameters through the model to generate a distribution of the output flux, from which uncertainty bounds (e.g., 95% confidence intervals) can be derived.",
      "The most common approach for UQ in this field is the error propagation method, often based on the Taylor series expansion (first-order, second-moment method). This method calculates the variance of the flux (\u03c3\u00b2_F) based on the variances of the input variables (\u03c3\u00b2_xi) and their partial derivatives with respect to the flux function f(...): \u03c3\u00b2_F \u2248 \u03a3(\u2202f/\u2202xi)\u00b2\u03c3\u00b2_xi."
    ],
    "justification": "The paper is a methodological review specifically about uncertainty quantification. It explicitly discusses and describes several formal probabilistic methods. The evidence clearly mentions \"Bayesian inference\" to produce a \"posterior probability distribution of the flux,\" which is the defining criterion for Level 3. It also describes other probabilistic methods like Monte Carlo simulations that operate on full probability distributions and formal error propagation, further solidifying its high-level treatment of uncertainty.",
    "paper_doi": "10.1016/j.trac.2025.118538",
    "paper_title": "Uncertainty in air-water mercury exchange flux measurements: A methodological review"
