      "To reconstruct the paleo-bathymetry of Prydz Bay, we employed a 2D backstripping technique. This method accounts for the physical effects of sediment loading and compaction, as well as the long-term thermal subsidence of the continental margin following rifting.",
      "Crucially, we corrected for the effects of Glacial Isostatic Adjustment (GIA) by incorporating ice sheet history models. This correction accounts for the visco-elastic response of the solid Earth to the changing mass of the Antarctic Ice Sheet, a dominant factor in the vertical motion of the crust in this region.",
      "The GIA models used are driven by mass balance changes between the cryosphere and the ocean, thereby linking the regional crustal deformation to the global budget of ice and water through geological time."
    ],
    "justification": "The paper's topic, reconstructing paleo-bathymetry in a glaciated margin, necessitates the application of physical models to account for sediment compaction, thermal subsidence, and glacial isostatic adjustment (GIA). The evidence indicates the use of GIA models, which are fundamentally based on the physics of a visco-elastic Earth responding to surface mass loads. These models inherently monitor global mass budgets (ice sheet volume vs. ocean volume) to calculate crustal deformation. This demonstrates the presence of primary physics and the monitoring of global budgets, which aligns with Level 2 criteria. The study is an application of these principles to a geological problem, rather than a development of a new, strictly conservative numerical framework with full adjoint consistency, which would be required for Level 3. It clearly surpasses Level 1, which would ignore or use overly simplistic empirical relationships for these critical physical processes.",
    "paper_doi": "10.1016/j.margeo.2025.107674",
    "paper_title": "Paleo-bathymetric Evolution of Prydz Bay since the Eocene-Oligocene Boundary, East Antarctica"
  },
