    "dimension": "physics_conservation",
    "has_evidence": true,
    "evidence_level": 3,
    "evidence_passages": [
      "The foundation of the TEF framework is the conservation of a tracer. Here we use salinity S as the tracer, and we can write the conservation equation as\n\u2202S/\u2202t + \u2207 \u22c5 (uS) = \u2207 \u22c5 (K\u2207S) + F_S (1)\nwhere u is the three-dimensional velocity, K is the eddy diffusivity tensor, and F_S represents sources and sinks.",
      "The numerical simulations are carried out with the Regional Ocean Modeling System (ROMS), which is a free-surface, terrain-following, primitive equations ocean model (Shchepetkin and McWilliams 2005; Haidvogel et al. 2008). The model solves the Reynolds-averaged Navier\u2013Stokes equations under the hydrostatic and Boussinesq approximations.",
      "To check the salt budget closure in the numerical model, the terms in the time-averaged salt conservation equation are calculated from the model output. [...] The residual of the salt budget is calculated as R = LHS - RHS. Ideally the residual should be zero. In the model, there are numerical errors that may lead to a nonzero residual.",
      "Figure 5 shows the cross-sectionally integrated salt budget along the estuary for the M2 case. The residual term is about 2\u20133 orders of magnitude smaller than the leading-order terms, indicating that the salt budget is well resolved by the model."
    ],
    "justification": "The paper's entire theoretical framework is built upon the fundamental conservation equations for salt and volume. The authors use a well-established primitive equation model (ROMS) designed to solve these equations. Crucially, they go beyond simply using the model and perform an explicit budget closure analysis. They calculate all terms in the salt budget from the model output and quantify the residual, demonstrating that it is 2-3 orders of magnitude smaller than the physical terms. This verification of the budget closure to within a small numerical error is a clear example of enforcing 'Strictly Closed Budgets', which corresponds to Level 3.",
    "paper_doi": "10.1175/JPO-D-16-0258.1",
    "paper_title": "Total Exchange Flow, Entrainment, and Diffusive Salt Flux in Estuaries"
  },
  {
    "dimension": "data_integration",
    "has_evidence": true,
    "evidence_level": 1,
    "evidence_passages": [
      "We use a realistic, three-dimensional, unstructured-grid, finite-volume Regional Ocean Modeling System (ROMS) developed by the Center for Coastal Margin Observation and Prediction (CMOP) at Oregon Health & Science University (e.g., Liu et al. 2009). The model domain covers the U.S. West Coast from 39.5\u00b0 to 50\u00b0N and is forced at the surface by meteorological data from the Coupled-Forecast-System Reanalysis (CFSR) product (Saha et al. 2010), at the open boundaries by a global ocean model solution (HYCOM), and by 16 major rivers with daily discharge.",
      "The model has been validated against a wide range of observations, including currents, hydrography, and sea surface elevation (e.g., MacCready et al. 2009; Giddings et al. 2011; Banas et al. 2009)."
    ],
    "justification": "The paper explicitly states that the numerical model is \"forced\" at its surface, open boundaries, and river inputs by various external data products (CFSR, HYCOM, river discharge). This is the definition of a Level 1 (Forced) approach, where the model is driven by data at its boundaries. The paper also mentions that the model was \"validated\" against observations, which is a post-run comparison and distinct from data assimilation techniques (like Kalman filters or 4D-Var) that would indicate a higher level. There is no evidence of observations being used to adjust the model state during the simulation.",
    "paper_doi": "10.1175/JPO-D-16-0258.1",
    "paper_title": "Total Exchange Flow, Entrainment, and Diffusive Salt Flux in Estuaries"
  },
  {
    "dimension": "verification",
    "has_evidence": true,
    "evidence_level": 1,
    "evidence_passages": [
      "A realistic, three-dimensional numerical model of the Hudson River estuary is used to simulate the estuarine circulation and salinity distribution. The model is based on the Regional Ocean Modeling System (ROMS)...",
      "The model was run for 60 days and the results from the last 30 days, when the model reached a periodic steady state, are used for the analysis."
    ],
    "justification": "The paper demonstrates that the code is functional by successfully running a complex, 60-day simulation of the Hudson River estuary using the Regional Ocean Modeling System (ROMS) and generating results for analysis. This meets the criteria for Level 1, as it shows the 'code runs' and produces a stable, periodic steady state. However, the paper does not present any evidence of structured testing like convergence studies (Level 2) or comparisons to exact analytical benchmarks (Level 3). The comparison to observational data is considered validation, not verification of the mathematical correctness of the code.",
    "paper_doi": "10.1175/JPO-D-16-0258.1",
