    "evidence_passages": [
      "To disentangle the sources of POC in the Lena River and delta, we applied a dual-carbon isotope mixing model (Fig. S1).",
      "The mixing model is based on the law of conservation of mass, according to which the \u03b413C and \u039414C values of a mixture reflect the proportional contribution of its sources...",
      "... we used the following mass balance equations: \u03b413Cmix = friverine \u00d7 \u03b413Criverine + fpermafrost \u00d7 \u03b413Cpermafrost + fphytoplankton \u00d7 \u03b413Cphytoplankton, (1) \u039414Cmix = friverine \u00d7 \u039414Criverine + fpermafrost \u00d7 \u039414Cpermafrost + fphytoplankton \u00d7 \u039414Cphytoplankton, (2) 1 = friverine + fpermafrost + fphytoplankton, (3)"
    ],
    "justification": "The paper uses a dual-carbon isotope mixing model which is explicitly stated to be \"based on the law of conservation of mass\" and employs \"mass balance equations\" to determine the proportional contribution of different sources to the total particulate organic carbon. This represents the presence of primary physics and the monitoring of a budget (the fractional composition of the mixture), which aligns with the criteria for Level 2. The budget is enforced within the context of the model (sum of fractions equals 1), but the study as a whole is observational and does not create a fully dynamic, prognostic model of the entire river system with strictly enforced conservation of mass and energy across all scales and processes, which would be required for Level 3.",
    "paper_doi": "10.5194/bg-20-1423-2023",
    "paper_title": "Particulate organic matter in the Lena River and its delta: from the permafrost catchment to the Arctic Ocean"
  },
  {
    "dimension": "data_integration",
    "has_evidence": true,
    "evidence_level": 3,
    "evidence_passages": [
      "We used a Bayesian mixing model, MixSIAR (Stock et al., 2018), to quantify the relative contributions of different OM sources to the POC pool in the Lena River main stem and the delta (Sect. 2.5).",
      "The model is based on the principle that a mixture's isotope composition reflects the composition of its sources, weighted by their proportional contribution to the mixture.",
      "The model uses a Markov chain Monte Carlo (MCMC) approach to generate posterior probability distributions for the source contributions that account for the uncertainty in source values, different fractionation factors, and the variability between and within the measured mixture values (Stock et al., 2018)."
    ],
    "justification": "The paper employs a Bayesian mixing model (MixSIAR) that uses a Markov chain Monte Carlo (MCMC) method to integrate observational data (isotope measurements) with a physical model principle (mass balance). The use of MCMC is explicitly cited as an example for Level 3. This approach represents a 'Synthesis' where the data (observations of isotopic composition) and the model physics (the mixing equation) are mathematically inseparable within the probabilistic framework to infer the contributions of different sources. The model doesn't just fit data (Level 1) or sequentially update a state (Level 2); it produces a holistic, probabilistic solution that is simultaneously consistent with the data, the model logic, and all associated uncertainties.",
    "paper_doi": "10.5194/bg-20-1423-2023",
    "paper_title": "Particulate organic matter in the Lena River and its delta: from the permafrost catchment to the Arctic Ocean"
  },
