    "evidence_passages": [
      "To disentangle the contribution of different OM sources to the POC pool, we used a three-end-member mixing model based on dual-carbon (\u039414C and \u03b413C) isotope signatures... We solved the system of three linear equations (Eqs. 1\u20133) using the R package \u201csiar\u201d (Stable Isotope Analysis in R; Parnell and Jackson, 2013).",
      "The model was run using the siarmcmcdirichlet function from the \u201csiar\u201d package with 100 000 iterations to calculate the most likely contribution of each source to the POC pool as a probability distribution."
    ],
    "justification": "The authors use a standard, published R package ('siar') to solve their isotopic mixing model, which provides a baseline level of trust in the mathematical implementation. More importantly, they specify the use of a Markov chain Monte Carlo (MCMC) function with a large number of iterations (100,000). Running a large number of iterations is a standard practice to ensure the MCMC simulation has converged to a stable posterior distribution. This practice serves as a form of convergence study, which is a key criterion for Level 2 ('Structured'). It demonstrates a structured approach to ensuring the numerical stability and reliability of their results, going beyond just running the code and getting an output (Level 1).",
    "paper_doi": "10.5194/bg-20-1423-2023",
    "paper_title": "Particulate organic matter in the Lena River and its delta: from the permafrost catchment to the Arctic Ocean"
