      "Dual-carbon (\u039414C and \u03b413C) isotope mixing model analyses indicated a significant phytoplankton contribution to deltaic POC (\u223c\u200968\u2009\u00b1\u20096\u2009%) and suggested an additional input of permafrost-derived OM into deltaic waters (\u223c\u200918\u2009\u00b1\u20094\u2009% of deltaic POC originates from Pleistocene deposits vs. \u223c\u20095\u2009\u00b1\u20094\u2009% in the river main stem).",
      "Despite the lower concentration of POC in the delta than in the main stem (0.41\u2009\u00b1\u20090.10 vs. 0.79\u2009\u00b1\u20090.30\u2009mg\u2009L\u22121, respectively), the amount of POC derived from Yedoma deposits in deltaic waters was almost twice as large as the amount of POC of Yedoma origin in the main stem (0.07\u2009\u00b1\u20090.02 and 0.04\u2009\u00b1\u20090.02\u2009mg\u2009L\u22121, respectively)."
    ],
    "justification": "The paper uses a dual-carbon isotope mixing model to estimate the contribution of different organic matter sources. The results of this model are presented with quantified uncertainties (e.g., \"68\u2009\u00b1\u20096\u2009%\", \"18\u2009\u00b1\u20094\u2009%\"). Modern isotope mixing models commonly use Bayesian statistical frameworks to generate posterior probability distributions for the source contributions, and the mean \u00b1 standard deviation format is a standard way to summarize these distributions. This method represents a formal, probabilistic approach to uncertainty quantification, which aligns with Level 3.",
    "paper_doi": "10.5194/bg-20-1423-2023",
