    "dimension": "physics_conservation",
    "has_evidence": true,
    "evidence_level": 2,
    "evidence_passages": [
      "This has been particularly true in the last decade, with the move to all-sky assimilation of microwave radiances, which has meant that the tangent-linear and adjoint of moist physics schemes are now a standard component of the 4D-Var minimization (Bauer et al., 2010; Geer et al., 2018)."
    ],
    "justification": "The paper analyzes the operational 4D-Var data assimilation system at ECMWF. The provided quote explicitly states that the tangent-linear and adjoint models of 'moist physics schemes' are a standard part of the minimization process. This indicates that primary physical processes are deeply integrated into the assimilation system, which is a key characteristic of Level 2 ('Primary physics present'). The 4D-Var method seeks a 'best fit' model trajectory by minimizing a cost function, which adjusts the model state to better match observations. This adjustment process, or analysis increment, is not constrained to strictly conserve physical quantities like mass or energy. The paper's focus on iterative methods (outer loops) to handle nonlinearities shows the system strives for consistency with the full physics but does not achieve the 'Strictly Closed Budgets' required for Level 3. Therefore, the evidence points to a system where primary physics are present, but conservation is not strictly enforced by the assimilation algorithm itself, aligning with Level 2.",
    "paper_doi": "10.5194/NPG-25-713-2018",
    "paper_title": "Nonlinear effects in 4D-Var"
  },
  {
    "dimension": "data_integration",
    "has_evidence": true,
    "evidence_level": 3,
    "evidence_passages": [
      "The ability of a data assimilation system to deal effectively with nonlinearities arising from the prognostic model or the relationship between the control variables and the available observations has received a lot of attention in theoretical studies based on very simplified test models.",
      "In this paper we analyse the nonlinear effects present in ECMWF 4D-Var and evaluate the ability of the incremental formulation to solve the nonlinear assimilation problem in a realistic NWP environment.",
      "Incremental 4D-Var is well suited for dealing with these nonlinear effects, but at the cost of increasing the number of outer loop relinearisations."
    ],
    "justification": "The paper explicitly discusses and analyzes the 4D-Var data assimilation method. 4D-Var is the canonical example of a Level 3 'Synthesis' approach, where observations and the prognostic model physics are combined in a mathematically inseparable way within a single cost function minimized over a time window. The abstract refers to this integration as dealing with nonlinearities arising from the 'prognostic model' and the 'relationship between the control variables and the available observations'.",
    "paper_doi": "10.5194/NPG-25-713-2018",
    "paper_title": "Nonlinear effects in 4D-Var"
  },
  {
    "dimension": "verification",
    "has_evidence": true,
    "evidence_level": 3,
    "evidence_passages": [
      "This is similar to what is routinely done in the development of new tangent linear and adjoint model code, where a Taylor test is performed to check the correctness of the linearised code, i.e. to check that the tangent linear model evolution is a good first-order approximation of the nonlinear model evolution for a small-enough perturbation."
    ],
    "justification": "The paper explicitly states that a 'Taylor test is performed to check the correctness of the linearised code'. The Taylor test is a rigorous mathematical check to ensure the accuracy of the tangent linear model, which is fundamental for calculating the gradient of the cost function in 4D-Var. This directly corresponds to the Level 3 criterion 'Adjoint/Taylor tests for gradient accuracy', which assesses the mathematical correctness of the core algorithms.",
    "paper_doi": "10.5194/NPG-25-713-2018",
    "paper_title": "Nonlinear effects in 4D-Var"
  },
  {
    "dimension": "validation",
    "has_evidence": true,
    "evidence_level": 2,
    "evidence_passages": [
      "Figure 7 shows the change in root mean square error (RMSE) of the 500 hPa geopotential height (Z500) forecast for the Northern and Southern Hemisphere extra-tropics as a function of forecast lead time. The results are based on a set of 4D-Var experiments run at TCo399 resolution (approx. 32 km horizontal grid spacing) and covering the period from 1 June to 31 August 2016 (276 assimilation cycles).",
      "The 4OL configuration is seen to bring a statistically significant improvement in forecast scores in both hemispheres and throughout the forecast range, with a peak improvement of around 0.5 % at day 4\u20135.",
      "Figure 8 is the same as Fig. 7 but for the 850 hPa vector wind (VW850) in the tropics. The impact on tropical winds is even more positive, with a statistically significant improvement of up to 1 % throughout the forecast range.",
      "Figure 9 shows the change in the mean fit of the analysis (i.e. at the start of the forecast) to various conventional and satellite observation types that are known to be sensitive to the model bias. It is seen that the additional outer loop has a mostly positive impact in reducing the mean observation-minus-background (O\u2212B) departures for most observation types."
    ],
    "justification": "The paper presents a quantitative validation of changes to the data assimilation system by assessing the impact on forecast skill. It explicitly uses global statistical metrics such as Root Mean Square Error (RMSE) and mean bias (fit to observations) to evaluate forecasts against real-world data (observations and the system's own analysis). This use of global RMSE and Bias metrics is a direct match for the Level 2 criteria.",
    "paper_doi": "10.5194/NPG-25-713-2018",
    "paper_title": "Nonlinear effects in 4D-Var"
  },
  {
    "dimension": "uncertainty_quantification",
    "has_evidence": false,
    "evidence_level": null,
    "evidence_passages": [],
    "justification": "The paper focuses on diagnosing the degree of nonlinearity in the 4D-Var data assimilation system and the effectiveness of the incremental approach in finding the minimum of the cost function. While it frames the 4D-Var problem in a probabilistic context (seeking the maximum a posteriori estimate) and mentions the use of an Ensemble of Data Assimilations (EDA) to construct the background error covariance matrix, the core analysis is about the optimization process. The paper does not present any methods or results related to quantifying the uncertainty, confidence, or error bounds of the resulting analysis state. Its focus is on the challenge of finding the single best-fit state in a nonlinear system, not on characterizing the probability distribution around that state.",
    "paper_doi": "10.5194/NPG-25-713-2018",
    "paper_title": "Nonlinear effects in 4D-Var"
  },
  {
    "dimension": "numerical_fidelity",
    "has_evidence": true,
    "evidence_level": 2,
    "evidence_passages": [
      "In its operational implementation at ECMWF (Rabier et al., 2000; Mahfouf and Rabier, 2000), the cost function increments are computed using a sequence of lower-resolution versions of the full nonlinear model M...",
      "It is important to note that the resolution of the second outer loop has been kept constant for diagnostic purposes throughout the period, while the resolution of the outer-loop nonlinear model has steadily increased from T L 799 (\u223c 25 km) in 2008 to T L 1279 (\u223c 9 km) today."
    ],
    "justification": "The paper describes the operational data assimilation system at ECMWF. The evidence indicates a multi-resolution approach, where the minimization is performed using 'a sequence of lower-resolution versions of the full nonlinear model'. The full nonlinear model itself is run at a high resolution ('T L 1279 (\u223c 9 km)'). This use of varying resolutions for computational efficiency, combined with a high-resolution outer loop, is a form of grid refinement characteristic of a Level 2 system. The model is global, so boundary handling is not a primary concern, but the high resolution implies realistic topography.",
