    "dimension": "physics_conservation",
    "has_evidence": true,
    "evidence_level": 2,
    "evidence_passages": [
      "In this study, the vertical displacements caused by atmospheric loading (ATML) are obtained from the German Research Centre for Geosciences (GFZ). The ATML displacements are computed by convolving global atmospheric pressure data with the elastic load Green\u2019s functions for a spherically symmetric, non-rotating, elastic and isotropic (SNREI) Earth model (Farrell 1972) in the centre of mass of the solid Earth frame (CM) (Blewitt 2003).",
      "The effect of NTOL is computed by convolving the bottom pressure with the load Green\u2019s functions for the CM frame. It is worth noting that the total mass of ocean in ECCO model is conserved.",
      "To quantitatively evaluate the consistency between the loading models and GPS observations, we calculated the weighted root-mean-square (WRMS) reductions after correcting the loading effects from GPS time-series... We first removed the combined loading effects (HYDL + ATML + NTOL) from the GPS time-series..."
    ],
    "justification": "The paper uses established, physics-based models to explain observed crustal deformation. The methodology is rooted in the physical principle of elastic deformation in response to surface mass loading, calculated by convolving mass data (atmosphere, ocean, hydrology) with Green's functions. This represents the 'Primary physics present' criterion for Level 2. The authors explicitly construct a 'budget' of deformation by summing the contributions from atmospheric, non-tidal ocean, and hydrological loading (`HYDL + ATML + NTOL`) and comparing this sum to the observed GPS signal. This demonstrates that 'global budgets [are] monitored'. The paper also explicitly notes that the ocean model used (ECCO) conserves mass. However, the budget is not 'strictly enforced' in a fully coupled or adjoint sense as required for Level 3; rather, the different loading models are run independently, their effects are summed, and the residual is analyzed. This process of modeling components, summing them, and comparing to reality fits the description of Level 2.",
    "paper_doi": "10.1093/GJI/GGX246",
    "paper_title": "Regional characteristics and influencing factors of seasonal vertical crustal motions in Yunnan, China"
  },
  {
    "dimension": "data_integration",
    "has_evidence": true,
    "evidence_level": 1,
    "evidence_passages": [
      "To estimate the vertical velocities and seasonal (annual and semi-annual) terms, we fit the daily position time-series of each station with the following function (e.g. Blewitt & Lavall\u00b4ee 2002): y(ti) = a + bti + c sin(2\u03c0ti) + d cos(2\u03c0ti) + e sin(4\u03c0ti) + f cos(4\u03c0ti) + vi, where ti is the epoch in years, y(ti) is the vertical position at epoch ti, a is the initial position, b is the linear rate, c and d are the annual terms, e and f are the semi-annual terms, and vi is the residual.",
      "To investigate the contribution of the environmental loading effects to the observed seasonal vertical motions, we compare the annual amplitudes and phases of the vertical displacements derived from the GPS time-series and the sum of the loading models (APL + NTOL + HYDL).",
      "After removing the loading effects from the GPS time-series, the WRMS (weighted root-mean-square) of the GPS time-series are reduced at most of the stations (Fig. 6), indicating that the environmental loading models can explain a considerable part of the seasonal signals in the GPS height time-series."
    ],
    "justification": "The study's methodology involves two separate steps. First, an empirical model (a function with linear, annual, and semi-annual terms) is fit directly to the observational GPS data to extract seasonal signals. This is a purely data-driven approach. Second, physical loading models (atmospheric, oceanic, hydrological) are used to generate independent predictions of crustal motion. The 'integration' of data and model logic consists of a direct comparison between these two results, and subtracting the model prediction from the observational data to analyze the residuals. This process is characteristic of a Level 1 'Forced' approach, where the model of observed motion is driven entirely by the data, and physical models are used as an external correction or for post-processing comparison, rather than being integrated into the state estimation itself. There is no evidence of sequential updates (Level 2) or a joint, inseparable synthesis of data and physics (Level 3).",
    "paper_doi": "10.1093/GJI/GGX246",
    "paper_title": "Regional characteristics and influencing factors of seasonal vertical crustal motions in Yunnan, China"
  },
  {
    "dimension": "verification",
    "has_evidence": true,
    "evidence_level": 2,
    "evidence_passages": [
      "To ensure the reliability of the solutions, we compared the daily coordinates of three IGS sites (LHAS, KUNM and WUHN) with the time-series published by the Scripps Orbit and Permanent Array Center (SOPAC; http://sopac.ucsd.edu). The WRMS of the differences for the three components are all less than 3 mm, which indicates our solutions are reliable."
    ],
    "justification": "The authors verify the output of their GPS data processing pipeline by comparing their calculated station coordinates with an independent, standard solution provided by SOPAC. This comparison against a trusted external benchmark for a subset of the data is a form of regression or consistency testing, which aligns with the structured verification practices described in Level 2. It goes beyond simply ensuring the code runs (Level 1) by actively checking the numerical correctness of the results against a known standard.",
    "paper_doi": "10.1093/GJI/GGX246",
    "paper_title": "Regional characteristics and influencing factors of seasonal vertical crustal motions in Yunnan, China"
  },
  {
    "dimension": "validation",
    "has_evidence": true,
    "evidence_level": 2,
    "evidence_passages": [
      "To assess the contribution of the environmental loading models to the observed seasonal vertical displacements, we compute the WRMS (weighted root-mean-square) of the GPS time-series before and after subtracting the modelled loading effects... Table 2 lists the WRMS of the GPS vertical time-series before and after correction for the loading models. The WRMS reduction is calculated by WRMS reduction = (WRMS_GPS \u2212 WRMS_res)/WRMS_GPS \u00d7 100 per cent, where WRMS_GPS and WRMS_res are the WRMS of the original GPS time-series and the residuals after subtracting the loading effects, respectively.",
      "To better quantify the agreement between observations and models, we calculate the correlation coefficients between the GPS observations and loading models (Table 3).",
      "Fig. 6 shows the comparison between GPS observations and the loading models for 12 selected GPS stations in different regions of Yunnan. From Fig. 6 we can see that the combined loading model can explain most of the seasonal signals in the GPS observations, especially for stations in central and southern Yunnan, such as KMIN, YNRL, YNTC and YNWS stations. The phase of the combined loading model is generally in agreement with the GPS observations."
    ],
    "justification": "The paper quantitatively validates loading models against real-world GPS data using standard statistical metrics. The authors calculate and report the Weighted Root-Mean-Square (WRMS), a variant of RMSE, and correlation coefficients to assess the agreement between the model and observations. This use of statistical metrics like WRMS reduction and correlation to evaluate the model fit for each time series directly corresponds to the Level 2 criteria: 'Statistical: Global RMSE and Bias metrics'. The paper also includes visual 'eyeball' comparisons of time series plots, which aligns with Level 1, but the quantitative statistical analysis is the primary method of validation, thus supporting Level 2.",
    "paper_doi": "10.1093/GJI/GGX246",
    "paper_title": "Regional characteristics and influencing factors of seasonal vertical crustal motions in Yunnan, China"
  },
  {
