    "has_evidence": true,
    "evidence_level": 3,
    "evidence_passages": [
      "Then we use the QOCA software to model the GPS time series with a functional model that includes a secular velocity, annual and semi-annual sinusoidal terms, and offsets due to earthquakes or instrument changes... The uncertainties of the parameters are determined using the least-squares method. The errors of the vertical seasonal amplitudes are generally smaller than 0.8 mm.",
      "Table 1 lists the amplitudes and phases of the annual and semi-annual vertical crustal motions in Yunnan, along with their 1-\u03c3 uncertainties.",
      "The errors represent one standard deviation."
    ],
    "justification": "The paper uses a formal statistical method, least-squares fitting, to model GPS time series and estimate parameters such as the amplitude of seasonal motion. This method also calculates the formal uncertainties (1-\u03c3 standard deviations) for these estimated parameters, which are reported in tables. This approach represents a formal, probabilistic quantification of parameter uncertainty derived from a statistical model and the data's noise characteristics. It is not heuristic (Level 1) or based on an ensemble spread (Level 2). It provides a probability distribution (implicitly Gaussian in this context) for the parameters, which aligns with the description of a Level 3 (Probabilistic) approach.",
    "paper_doi": "10.1093/GJI/GGX246",
