      "The ocean model used in this study is the Regional Oceanic Modeling System (ROMS), which is a free-surface, terrain-following, primitive equations ocean model (Shchepetkin and McWilliams, 2005). The model uses the hydrostatic and Boussinesq approximations...",
      "At the open boundaries, the model uses a combination of radiation and nudging conditions (Marchesiello et al., 2001).",
      "Heat flux is parameterized using bulk formulae, and a relaxation term is added to the net heat flux in order to nudge the model SST towards the observed one. The relaxation coefficient is \u221240 W m\u22122 \u00b0C\u22121 (Barnier et al., 1995).",
      "A similar restoring term is used to nudge the model SSS to the observed one using a piston velocity of 1.36 \u00d7 10\u22125 m s\u22121 (or 40 m/90 days)."
    ],
    "justification": "The paper states that the model (ROMS) is based on primitive equations with hydrostatic and Boussinesq approximations, which constitutes 'Primary physics'. However, it also explicitly describes the use of 'nudging' at the open boundaries and 'relaxation' or 'restoring' terms for sea surface temperature (SST) and salinity (SSS). These nudging terms introduce artificial sources and sinks of heat and salt to prevent model drift, meaning the system's budgets are not strictly closed or conserved. This combination of a physically-based core with non-conservative forcing terms aligns with the Level 2 criteria: 'Primary physics present; global budgets monitored but not strictly enforced'.",
    "paper_doi": "10.1016/J.POCEAN.2019.04.012",
