    "dimension": "validation",
    "has_evidence": true,
    "evidence_level": 2,
    "evidence_passages": [
      "The model skill is evaluated by comparing the simulated monthly mean Sea Surface Temperature (SST) and Sea Surface Height (SSH) with the corresponding observations. The SST monthly climatology from the model is compared to the Pathfinder Advanced Very High Resolution Radiometer (AVHRR) SST monthly climatology...",
      "For a quantitative evaluation of the model skill, we compute the domain-averaged Root Mean Square Error (RMSE) and Bias of the seasonal mean SST (model minus observation). The RMSE is about 0.5 \u00b0C in winter and spring, increases to 0.7 \u00b0C in summer, and decreases to 0.6 \u00b0C in autumn. The bias is very small and ranges between 0.04 and 0.1 \u00b0C in the four seasons.",
      "The model simulated SSH is compared with the Archiving, Validation and Interpretation of Satellite Oceanographic data (AVISO) merged product.",
      "The domain-averaged RMSE of the seasonal mean SSH is about 2.7 cm in winter, 2.5 cm in spring, 3.2 cm in summer and 3.0 cm in autumn. The bias is very small and ranges between 0.01 and 0.1 cm in the four seasons."
    ],
    "justification": "The paper validates the model against independent observational datasets (AVHRR for SST and AVISO for SSH). While it includes qualitative, 'eyeball' comparisons of seasonal maps (Level 1 evidence), it explicitly calculates and reports domain-averaged, global statistical metrics: Root Mean Square Error (RMSE) and Bias. This quantitative evaluation using global metrics directly meets the criteria for Level 2.",
    "paper_doi": "10.1016/J.POCEAN.2019.04.012",
    "paper_title": "The impact of climate change on circulation patterns in the Eastern Mediterranean Sea upper layer using Med-ROMS model"
