      "The wave attenuation by sea ice is parameterized in WW3 following Ardhuin et al. (2015) and Stopa et al. (2016). This parameterization, based on empirical relationships, has been shown to provide realistic estimates of the wave attenuation rate in the MIZ (see, e.g., Ardhuin et al., 2016, 2017; Stopa et al., 2018a).",
      "The lateral melt rate U_lat (in m s\u22121) is parameterized following the formulation of Steele (1992), which depends on the floe size.",
      "The change in floe size distribution is also parameterized. The maximum floe size is limited by the wave-induced fragmentation. Based on the observations of a characteristic floe size of \u223c 100 m in the MIZ (e.g., Stern et al., 2018a), we choose to limit the maximum floe size to this value in the presence of waves (significant wave height > 0.5 m).",
      "Our results also suggest that the coupling between waves and sea ice would ultimately need to be investigated in a more complex system, allowing for interactions with the ocean and the atmosphere."
    ],
    "justification": "The model described in the paper couples two existing physical models (NEMO and WW3), but the novel interactions between them rely heavily on parameterizations and empirical relationships, which directly maps to the Level 1 criterion of 'Empirical or 'Nudged' physics'. For instance, wave attenuation by sea ice is described as a 'parameterization, based on empirical relationships'. Similarly, lateral melt and floe size distribution are also 'parameterized'. There is no mention of monitoring or enforcing the closure of energy, mass, or momentum budgets across the coupled components, which is another hallmark of Level 1. The authors' conclusion that the system needs to be investigated further in a more complex model also suggests that the current implementation is not a fully consistent or conservative system.",
