    "has_evidence": true,
    "evidence_level": 3,
    "evidence_passages": [
      "The coupled DA scheme of AWI-CPS is an ensemble-based system, which is based on the Parallel Data Assimilation Framework (PDAF, Nerger & Hiller, 2013). PDAF provides an implementation of the Local Error Subspace Transform Kalman Filter (LESTKF, Nerger et al., 2012), which is an efficient variant of the ensemble Kalman filter (EnKF, Evensen, 2003) for high-dimensional models.",
      "Each forecast consists of 30 ensemble members.",
      "The forecast probability is calculated as the fraction of ensemble members with SIC above 15%.",
      "Figure 11 shows the reliability diagram for the Arctic sea\u2010ice probability forecasts for different lead times. The reliability diagram plots the observed frequency against the forecast probability for specific probability bins (e.g., 0%\u201310%, 10%\u201320%, etc.), showing how well the predicted probabilities correspond to the actual outcomes.",
      "In addition, we compare the rank histograms (Talagrand diagrams) of the assimilated sea\u2010ice concentration in the Arctic and Antarctic (Figure 4). A U\u2010shaped rank histogram indicates that the observation is too often outside of the ensemble range, meaning the ensemble spread is too small to represent the full uncertainty. In contrast, a dome\u2010shaped histogram shows that the ensemble spread is too large. A flat histogram indicates a reliable ensemble with appropriate spread."
    ],
    "justification": "The paper uses a 30-member ensemble within a Local Error Subspace Transform Kalman Filter (LESTKF), which is a variant of the Ensemble Kalman Filter (EnKF). The EnKF is a formal, probabilistic data assimilation method that uses an ensemble to approximate the error covariance matrix, representing the prior and posterior distributions within a Bayesian framework. The authors then use this ensemble to generate explicit probabilistic forecasts (e.g., \"forecast probability is calculated as the fraction of ensemble members\"). Crucially, they evaluate the quality of these probabilistic forecasts using formal statistical tools like reliability diagrams and rank histograms, which are designed to assess how well an ensemble's spread represents the true uncertainty. This methodology goes beyond simply using ensemble spread as a proxy for error (Level 2) and represents a formal probabilistic approach to uncertainty quantification, consistent with Level 3.",
