    "evidence_passages": [
      "The vertical ablation rate m (in m/s) of the ice shelf front is directly proportional to the thermal driving, \u0394T = Ta \u2212 Tf, where Ta is the ambient water temperature and Tf is the in situ freezing temperature of seawater. In its simplest form, the melt rate is given by m = c_p * \u03c1_w * \u03b3_T * u* * \u0394T / (\u03c1_i * L_f), where c_p is the specific heat capacity of seawater, \u03c1_w and \u03c1_i are the densities of seawater and ice, respectively, \u03b3_T is the turbulent exchange coefficient for heat (Stanton number), u* is the friction velocity, and L_f is the latent heat of fusion for ice.",
      "A first\u2010order effect of the freshwater wedge is the baroclinic shear that it induces. Assuming that the Ross Ice Shelf front is a north\u2010south oriented vertical boundary, the geostrophic velocity anomaly, relative to the velocity at some reference depth, can be estimated using the thermal wind equations: \u2202u/\u2202z = -g/(f*\u03c1_0) * \u2202\u03c1/\u2202y and \u2202v/\u2202z = g/(f*\u03c1_0) * \u2202\u03c1/\u2202x.",
      "The water column immediately adjacent to the ice shelf front will be stratified due to the presence of the buoyant meltwater plume, and this will cause the isopycnals to tilt downward toward the ice shelf front. This structure forms the basis of the freshwater wedge that is the subject of this paper."
    ],
    "justification": "The paper is an observational study that explains a natural phenomenon using primary physical principles. It explicitly uses equations for thermodynamics (melt rate based on thermal driving and heat exchange) and geophysical fluid dynamics (thermal wind equations for geostrophic shear) to analyze field data. This demonstrates that 'Primary physics [are] present'. The analysis involves calculating components of heat, salt, and momentum budgets (e.g., melt rate, density changes, velocity shear) based on observations, which aligns with 'global budgets monitored'. However, as an observational study of an open system rather than a closed numerical model, it does not feature the 'strictly enforced' budgets or the specific numerical methods (Adjoint/Finite Element) required for Level 3. It surpasses Level 1 because its core mechanism is based on fundamental physical laws, not purely empirical relationships.",
    "paper_doi": "10.1029/2018JC014594",
    "paper_title": "A Wedge Mechanism for Summer Surface Water Inflow Into the Ross Ice Shelf Cavity"
  },
