    "dimension": "physics_conservation",
    "has_evidence": true,
    "evidence_level": 3,
    "evidence_passages": [
      "The most commonly applied ecosystem modelling tool in the Barents Sea is the Ecopath with Ecosim (EwE) software package... EwE combines a static mass-balance model of the food web (Ecopath) coupled with a dynamic simulation module (Ecosim). The Ecopath approach describes the ecosystem at a specific point in time by a set of linear equations, based on the fundamental assumption of mass balance within the system... The core of the routine is the balancing of the model, by which production and consumption rates of all groups are constrained to ensure that the energy inputs and outputs of each group are balanced and that consumption does not exceed production within the system (Christensen and Walters 2004).",
      "The Atlantis modelling framework is a full end-to-end model that represents all parts of a marine ecosystem, including physical, chemical, ecological and fisheries processes... The model represents the physical environment by a set of dynamically connected polygons, with vertical stratification defined by a number of layers. Water fluxes between polygons and layers are derived from a Regional Ocean Modelling System (ROMS), which ensures a realistic representation of the hydrographic conditions (Hansen et al. 2016)... The biological model is based on nutrient dynamics, where biomass is tracked in both nitrogen and carbon."
    ],
    "justification": "The paper describes the use of ecosystem models that are explicitly built on conservation principles. The Ecopath with Ecosim (EwE) model is founded on the 'fundamental assumption of mass balance,' ensuring that 'energy inputs and outputs of each group are balanced.' The Atlantis model uses hydrodynamics from a Regional Ocean Modelling System (ROMS)\u2014a model based on physical conservation laws\u2014to drive transport. Furthermore, its biological component is 'based on nutrient dynamics, where biomass is tracked in both nitrogen and carbon.' Tracking conserved currencies like elemental nitrogen and carbon and ensuring energy balance are hallmarks of a system with strictly closed budgets. This adherence to conservation of mass and energy, coupled with physically consistent transport from a model like ROMS, directly supports the Level 3 criteria of 'Strictly Closed Budgets' and 'consistency across all scales.'",
    "paper_doi": "10.1007/978-3-030-28404-6_3",
    "paper_title": "Arctic Marine Ecosystems, Climate Change Impacts, and Governance Responses: An Integrated Perspective from the Barents Sea"
  },
