    "evidence_level": 2,
    "evidence_passages": [
      "Coupled regional climate models (RCMs) driven by different GCMs under the A1B emission scenario projected a continuous decline of annual mean sea-ice extent throughout the twenty-first century, with the Barents Sea becoming seasonally ice-free somewhere between 2040 and 2060 (Koenigk et al. 2013).",
      "Based on a single-species assessment model, a recent study has projected the development of Northeast Arctic cod biomass and yield for the period 2017\u20132040 under different climate and fishing mortality scenarios (Hjermann et al. 2017). The authors found that under a \u2018business-as-usual\u2019 scenario of fishing mortality, a projected moderate warming would result in increased biomass and yield, while a strong warming scenario would lead to a slight decrease.",
      "Due to the large uncertainties attached to future climate change and its ecological consequences, but also related to future fisheries and other human pressures, ecosystem models are increasingly used to explore the range of plausible future developments rather than for making precise quantitative predictions of a single future state."
    ],
    "justification": "The paper describes and relies on studies that use ensemble-based approaches to quantify uncertainty. Specifically, it mentions the use of different Global Climate Models (GCMs) to drive regional models, which constitutes a multi-model ensemble. It also frequently refers to the use of different climate and fishing scenarios (e.g., IPCC emission scenarios, warming levels) to explore a range of plausible outcomes. This use of model ensembles and sensitivity to different scenarios to understand the spread of potential futures is characteristic of a Level 2 approach to uncertainty quantification.",
    "paper_doi": "10.1007/978-3-030-28404-6_3",
    "paper_title": "Arctic Marine Ecosystems, Climate Change Impacts, and Governance Responses: An Integrated Perspective from the Barents Sea"
