    "evidence_passages": [
      "In order to ensure the accuracy and reliability of the numerical model in this article, the numerical wave tank is first verified. The simulation results of the wave surface are compared with the theoretical results of the fifth-order Stokes wave. The specific parameters are as follows: the water depth d is 10 m, the wave height H is 1.2 m, and the period T is 4.4 s. Figure 4 shows the comparison between the numerical simulation of the wave surface at the inlet of the numerical wave tank and the theoretical value of the fifth-order Stokes wave. It can be seen from the figure that the numerical simulation results are in good agreement with the theoretical values, and the maximum error is within 3%, which verifies the accuracy and effectiveness of the numerical model.",
      "In the numerical simulation process, the density of the grid has a significant impact on the accuracy and efficiency of the calculation. In order to ensure that the calculation results do not change with the change of the grid density, the grid independence verification is carried out. Three different grid numbers are selected, namely grid 1 (8.32\u00d710^5), grid 2 (1.25\u00d710^6), and grid 3 (1.92\u00d710^6). The horizontal force on the single pile under the three grid densities is compared. Figure 5 shows the time history curve of the horizontal wave force on the single pile under the three grid densities. It can be seen from the figure that the results of grid 2 and grid 3 are very close, and the maximum relative error of the horizontal force is 1.6%. Considering the calculation accuracy and efficiency, grid 2 is selected for subsequent numerical simulation research."
    ],
    "justification": "The paper provides two key pieces of evidence for Level 2. First, it performs a grid independence study by testing three different mesh densities to ensure the results are converged, which directly corresponds to the 'convergence studies' criterion. Second, the authors verify their numerical wave tank by comparing the simulated wave surface against the theoretical fifth-order Stokes wave theory, which acts as a form of regression or benchmark test. These structured verification steps go beyond merely running the code (Level 1) but do not include the more rigorous algorithmic checks like adjoint/Taylor tests required for Level 3.",
