    "evidence_passages": [
      "The time series of the vertical component for each GNSS station is described using the following functional model: l(t) = a + bt + \u03a3(cj sin(\u03c9jt) + dj cos(\u03c9jt)) + e, where l(t) is the observation at epoch t, a is the initial position, b is the linear velocity, cj and dj are the amplitudes of the periodic signals, \u03c9j is the corresponding angular frequency, and e is the observation error.",
      "To derive a continuous VCD field from discrete GNSS stations, we performed the GNSS imaging technique, which is a generalized method based on the least-squares principle (e.g., Davis et al. 1997; Haines and Holt 1993; Shen et al. 1996; Wu et al. 2011).",
      "The basic principle of the GNSS imaging technique is least-squares collocation (LSC), and it can be used to estimate the continuous VCD field by combining the discrete GNSS observations and a prior covariance function of the crustal deformation field."
    ],
    "justification": "The paper's methodology relies on an empirical, statistical approach rather than a model based on first-principles physics. The core method is \"GNSS imaging,\" which uses a functional model (linear trend plus sinusoids) to fit time-series data and least-squares collocation (LSC) to interpolate these results into a continuous field. This is a data-fitting and statistical interpolation technique. It does not incorporate or enforce physical laws such as conservation of mass or equations of continuum mechanics. While the results are interpreted in the context of physical processes (like GIA and surface loading), the model itself does not simulate these processes or ensure that any physical budgets are closed. This corresponds to Level 1, which is characterized by empirical physics where budgets are ignored.",
    "paper_doi": "10.1007/s00024-022-03144-3",
