    "evidence_passages": [
      "To obtain the spatial patterns of vertical crustal deformation in South America, we use the global navigation satellite system (GNSS) imaging method based on the least-squares collocation (LSC) algorithm to process the GNSS vertical time series from 2010 to 2020.",
      "The GNSS imaging method is a spatial interpolation algorithm based on the LSC method. In this method, the covariance function is used to describe the spatial correlation of the observed data, and then the regional vertical crustal deformation is obtained by spatial interpolation based on the LSC method.",
      "The basic principle of the LSC method is to separate the trend term and the random signal from the observations by the least-squares adjustment method and then predict the signal value at any point."
    ],
    "justification": "The paper uses the Least-Squares Collocation (LSC) method, which is described as a 'spatial interpolation algorithm'. This method generates a continuous spatial field of crustal deformation directly from discrete GNSS data points. The model is driven entirely by the data and its statistical covariance, without the integration of any underlying physical laws or process models. This approach directly aligns with the Level 1 (Forced) criteria, where the model is driven by data and physical constraints are not enforced.",
