      "To evaluate the spatial resolution and recovery ability of the GIM with the given SAM GNSS network, we conducted a checkerboard resolution test.",
      "The input model of the checkerboard resolution test is composed of 5\u00b0 \u00d7 5\u00b0 cells with alternating positive and negative vertical displacements of \u00b1 5 mm (Fig. 4a). Then, we computed the synthetic displacements at each GNSS station based on the in-put model and added random Gaussian noise with a standard deviation of 2 mm to the synthetic data. Finally, the synthetic data were inverted to obtain the recovered vertical displacement field (Fig. 4b).",
      "The recovered patterns show good consistency with the input model in most areas, but the amplitudes of the recovered signals are generally smaller than the input values."
    ],
    "justification": "The authors perform a checkerboard resolution test, which is a common type of synthetic data test used in geophysics to verify inversion codes. They create a known input model ('ground truth'), generate synthetic data from it, add noise, and then run their algorithm on this synthetic data. By comparing the recovered output to the known input, they verify the 'recovery ability' and thus the mathematical correctness of their implementation. This structured test, using a known input-output pair to evaluate the code's performance, is a form of regression testing that fits the criteria for Level 2.",
