      "Quality control of the digitized data included checks for transcription errors (e.g., repeated values and spikes), checks that monthly MSL agreed with published values (where available), and comparison to other nearby tide gauges (e.g., New York, NY; Portland, ME; and Saint John, Canada; see Supporting Information).",
      "To verify our results, we compare the amplitude and phase of the eight largest tidal constituents to the published NOAA values for the Boston tide gauge (station 8443970) for the 1983\u20132001 epoch (Table 2).",
      "Our calculated RSL rise from 1921 to 2017 is 2.87 \u00b1 0.17 mm/year (95% confidence), which is statistically indistinguishable from the NOAA published rate of 2.83 \u00b1 0.17 mm/year for the same period (NOAA, 2018), verifying our data processing and analysis methods."
    ],
    "justification": "The paper provides multiple examples of structured verification by comparing its results against established, external benchmarks, which is a form of regression testing. The authors explicitly state they 'verify our results' by comparing calculated tidal constituents against published NOAA values. They also confirm their overall methodology by showing that their calculated rate of relative sea-level rise is 'statistically indistinguishable' from the official NOAA rate, stating this process is 'verifying our data processing and analysis methods.' These practices directly align with the Level 2 criteria of using unit/regression tests against known benchmarks.",
