    "dimension": "uncertainty_quantification",
    "has_evidence": true,
    "evidence_level": 3,
    "evidence_passages": [
      "To quantify the overall uncertainty, we developed a Monte Carlo-style procedure that is conceptually similar to the approach used by Kopp et al., (2016). We drew 10,000 random samples from the distributions of each of the four error sources (Figure 4) and then summed the random errors in quadrature to produce a probability distribution of the total error for each year. The standard deviation of the resulting total error distribution is taken as the 1-\u03c3 error for the annual MSL value.",
      "Datum definition uncertainty arises because MHHW and MLLW are defined from an average over a 19 year tidal datum epoch, but we have at most a few months of data from any given year. To quantify this uncertainty, we use a bootstrapping approach. For each year from 1847-1921, we take the available high and low water measurements and bootstrap them (i.e. sample with replacement) 10,000 times to produce a distribution of MHHW, MLLW, and MSL.",
      "We used a weighted least-squares regression, in which each data point is weighted by the inverse of its variance (1/\u03c3^2), to estimate the linear rate of RSL change and its uncertainty over several time periods. The 95% confidence intervals on the rate were determined from the standard error of the slope, assuming a t-distribution."
    ],
    "justification": "The paper employs a formal, probabilistic approach to uncertainty quantification, which aligns with Level 3. The authors explicitly identify multiple sources of error, model them with probability distributions (e.g., assuming Gaussian distributions or deriving them via bootstrapping), and then propagate these uncertainties using a Monte Carlo simulation with 10,000 samples to generate a final probability distribution for the total error. The resulting uncertainties (variances) are then used to inform a weighted least-squares regression, and confidence intervals are formally calculated. This goes far beyond heuristic estimates (Level 1) or simple ensemble spreads (Level 2).",
