      "Figure 2b shows that the modeled net ocean C uptake is \u223c188 PgC, which is about 15% larger than the GCP estimate of \u223c164 PgC for 1782\u20132020 (GCP C budget for 1750\u20132020 minus emissions for 1750\u20131781). This difference is consistent with the known high-bias of ocean models, including the OCIM, in their estimates of oceanic C uptake (DeVries, 2022; Gruber et al., 2019).",
      "The resulting column inventory of C*ant for the year 2010 is shown in Figure 3a. This inventory is in good qualitative agreement with the observation-based estimate of Gruber et al. (2019), shown in Figure 3b."
    ],
    "justification": "The paper provides evidence for both Level 1 and Level 2 validation. Level 2 evidence is found in the quantitative comparison of global carbon inventories against the independent Global Carbon Project (GCP) data synthesis. The authors explicitly state their model's total simulated atmospheric CO2 increase and ocean carbon uptake and compare these values directly to GCP estimates, noting a specific bias for ocean uptake (\"about 15% larger\"). This use of global metrics and quantification of bias against real-world data aligns perfectly with the Level 2 criteria. Additionally, the paper provides Level 1 evidence by qualitatively comparing spatial patterns of anthropogenic carbon column inventories and air-sea fluxes against observation-based estimates, using subjective language such as \"good qualitative agreement.\" The highest level of evidence supported is Level 2.",
