      "To estimate the impact of RSL variability on flood frequency, we follow the approach proposed in previous works (e.g., Zanchettin et al. 2007; Lionello 2012; Marcos and Tsimplis 2008), where the observed daily maximum water levels at the PS tide-gauge station for the period 1872\u20132019 are used to fit a GEV probability distribution for each year, thus obtaining time-varying GEV parameters.",
      "We employ the Singular Spectrum Analysis (SSA; Ghil et al. 2002) to decompose the time series of the monthly mean RSL at the PS station into a long-term trend, a set of oscillatory components, and a residual noise. This technique identifies the main modes of variability of a time series without any a priori assumption on their analytical form (e.g., sinusoidal), and it is therefore particularly suitable for the analysis of climatic time series, where signals are typically quasi-periodic and modulated in amplitude."
    ],
    "justification": "The paper uses statistical models (Generalized Extreme Value distribution, Singular Spectrum Analysis) that are directly fitted to or derived from observational data. For instance, the GEV model parameters are determined by fitting the model to observed daily maximum water levels. Similarly, SSA is used to decompose the observed sea-level time series. This methodology is a clear example of a model being \"driven by data,\" which corresponds to the description of Level 1. The models are entirely empirical and determined by the observations, rather than integrating observations with an independent physical model.",
    "paper_doi": "10.1007/s10584-022-03448-2",
