    "justification": "The paper describes a machine learning pipeline (AutoTerm) for extracting glacier terminus positions from satellite imagery. This is a data processing and feature extraction task, not a physics-based simulation. The paper does not implement or discuss any physical laws, conservation principles (e.g., conservation of mass or energy), or budget closures. The generated data is intended for use in other models that might incorporate physics, but the method presented in this paper does not.",
    "paper_doi": "10.5194/tc-17-3485-2023",
    "paper_title": "AutoTerm: an automated pipeline for glacier terminus extraction using machine learning and a \u201cbig data\u201d repository of Greenland glacier termini"
  },
  {
    "dimension": "data_integration",
    "has_evidence": true,
    "evidence_level": 1,
    "evidence_passages": [
      "First, we leverage existing manually picked terminus traces (16\u2009440) as training data to significantly improve the generalization of the DL algorithm.",
      "We employ a deep learning neural network with a U-Net architecture to automate terminus delineation (Ronneberger et al., 2015). The U-Net is a convolutional neural network (CNN) that has previously been successful in segmenting glacier features such as calving fronts, supraglacial lakes, and crevasses...",
      "Our pipeline has successfully picked 278\u2009239 termini for 295 glaciers in Greenland from Landsat 5, 7, 8 and Sentinel-1 and Sentinel-2 images, spanning the period from 1984 to 2021."
    ],
    "justification": "The paper describes a deep learning (DL) model (a U-Net) to extract glacier terminus positions from satellite imagery. This model is purely data-driven; it is trained on a large dataset of manually identified terminus traces. The model learns to identify visual patterns in the data but does not incorporate any physical laws or principles of glacier dynamics. This directly corresponds to the Level 1 description: \"Model is driven by data; physics may be violated.\" The model's entire logic is based on fitting the training data, not on simulating a physical process.",
    "paper_doi": "10.5194/tc-17-3485-2023",
    "paper_title": "AutoTerm: an automated pipeline for glacier terminus extraction using machine learning and a \u201cbig data\u201d repository of Greenland glacier termini"
  },
  {
    "dimension": "verification",
    "has_evidence": true,
    "evidence_level": 2,
    "evidence_passages": [
      "To validate our pipeline, we randomly select 20 % of the manually picked termini as the test dataset, which is completely independent of the training and validation datasets. We compare the performance of AutoTerm with other DL-based studies by computing the mean absolute error (MAE) between the automatically and manually delineated terminus positions (Cheng et al., 2021; Gourmelon et al., 2022). The MAE of the AutoTerm pipeline is 79 m, which is less than 1 pixel size for Landsat (90 m) and comparable to other studies (Fig. 6a).",
      "We quantify the uncertainty of our DL model in two ways: (1) the model\u2019s confidence in its prediction, which is derived from the softmax probability of the U-Net model output, and (2) the geometric standard deviation, which captures the geometric complexity of the predicted terminus trace.",
      "The pipeline has been tested on glaciers in Greenland with an error of 79 m."
    ],
    "justification": "The paper provides strong evidence for Level 2 by describing a structured testing and validation process. The authors use a hold-out test dataset (20% of manually picked termini) to validate their pipeline, which is a standard practice analogous to regression testing in a machine learning context. They calculate a mean absolute error (MAE) of 79m by comparing their model's output against this 'ground truth' dataset. Furthermore, they implement a structured uncertainty quantification method to assess model confidence and geometric complexity. This systematic validation and error analysis against a known dataset goes beyond simple functionality (Level 1) and aligns with the structured testing required for Level 2. There is no evidence of Level 3 tests like adjoint/Taylor tests or comparison to exact analytical benchmarks.",
    "paper_doi": "10.5194/tc-17-3485-2023",
    "paper_title": "AutoTerm: an automated pipeline for glacier terminus extraction using machine learning and a \u201cbig data\u201d repository of Greenland glacier termini"
  },
  {
    "dimension": "validation",
    "has_evidence": true,
    "evidence_level": 3,
    "evidence_passages": [
      "To evaluate the model performance, we compared the AutoTerm-picked termini against manually delineated termini in the test dataset. We use the mean distance (MD) as the error metric, which is the mean of the shortest distance from each pixel on the manually delineated terminus to the AutoTerm-picked terminus. The model reached a mean distance of 79 m for the test dataset (Fig. 3a).",
      "We also test the model against an additional independent dataset of 260 manually picked termini for 130 glaciers in Greenland, from the MEaSUREs Greenland 6- and 12-Day Ice Velocity Grids, Version 2 dataset (Howat, 2021). The mean error is 110 m for this dataset (Fig. 3b)."
    ],
    "justification": "The paper first reports a global error metric (mean distance of 79 m) against a held-out test set, which meets the Level 2 criteria. It then goes beyond this by performing a blind validation against an 'additional independent dataset' from an external source (the MEaSUREs dataset). This dataset covers 130 glaciers across Greenland and was not used during model development. This constitutes a validation against an independent, global-scale (within the model's domain of Greenland) dataset, which fully satisfies the Level 3 criteria.",
    "paper_doi": "10.5194/tc-17-3485-2023",
    "paper_title": "AutoTerm: an automated pipeline for glacier terminus extraction using machine learning and a \u201cbig data\u201d repository of Greenland glacier termini"
  },
  {
    "dimension": "uncertainty_quantification",
    "has_evidence": true,
    "evidence_level": 3,
    "evidence_passages": [
      "We quantify the terminus position uncertainty by perturbing the input images and then measuring the standard deviation of the resulting terminus predictions (Fig. 5).",
      "Specifically, we use the Monte Carlo dropout method (Gal and Ghahramani, 2016) to perturb the input image. Monte Carlo dropout is a Bayesian approximation method that introduces stochasticity into the model by enabling dropout layers at test time. This is equivalent to sampling from the posterior distribution of the model weights.",
      "For each input image, we perform 100 forward passes of the model with dropout enabled to obtain 100 different terminus predictions (Fig. 5b). Then, we calculate the standard deviation of the 100 terminus predictions at each point along the terminus line to obtain a spatially varying uncertainty estimate (Fig. 5c)."
    ],
    "justification": "The paper implements Monte Carlo dropout, which is explicitly described as a 'Bayesian approximation method' that is 'equivalent to sampling from the posterior distribution of the model weights'. This technique uses an ensemble of 100 stochastic forward passes to approximate a posterior distribution over the model's output, from which uncertainty metrics (standard deviation) are derived. This use of a formal, albeit approximate, Bayesian method to derive uncertainty distributions aligns with the Level 3 criteria for 'Probabilistic: Formal Bayesian UQ; posterior distributions'.",
    "paper_doi": "10.5194/tc-17-3485-2023",
    "paper_title": "AutoTerm: an automated pipeline for glacier terminus extraction using machine learning and a \u201cbig data\u201d repository of Greenland glacier termini"
  },
  {
    "dimension": "numerical_fidelity",
    "has_evidence": true,
    "evidence_level": 3,
    "evidence_passages": [
      "In glaciology, the terminus is a dynamic feature that is highly variable in both space and time and marks the interface between a glacier and another medium such as ocean or land.",
      "Our pipeline has successfully picked 278\u2009239 termini for 295 glaciers in Greenland from Landsat 5, 7, 8 and Sentinel-1 and Sentinel-2 images, spanning the period from 1984 to 2021.",
      "The satellite imagery we used in this study includes Landsat 5 Thematic Mapper (TM) (30 m resolution), Landsat 7 Enhanced Thematic Mapper Plus (ETM+) (15 m panchromatic and 30 m multispectral), Landsat 8 Operational Land Imager (OLI) (15 m panchromatic and 30 m multispectral), Sentinel-1 C-band synthetic aperture radar (SAR) (10 m), and Sentinel-2 MultiSpectral Instrument (MSI) (10 m).",
      "The high sampling frequency and the controlled quality of our terminus data will enable better quantification of ice sheet change and model-based parameterizations of ice\u2013ocean interactions."
    ],
